1
00:00:00,980 --> 00:00:05,870
[LOGO MUSIC]

2
00:00:21,060 --> 00:00:22,470
NARRATOR: The
 following dramatization

3
00:00:22,470 --> 00:00:26,430
is based on personal interviews,
 books, newspapers, magazine

4
00:00:26,430 --> 00:00:29,130
accounts, and the reports of
 the Presidential Commission

5
00:00:29,130 --> 00:00:32,200
and the House Committee on
 the Challenger accident.

6
00:00:32,200 --> 00:00:34,450
This picture was researched
 with the consultation

7
00:00:34,450 --> 00:00:37,120
of the National Aeronautics
 and Space Administration

8
00:00:37,120 --> 00:00:39,220
and was filmed at the
 Johnson Space Center

9
00:00:39,220 --> 00:00:42,650
and at Clear Lake, Texas.

10
00:00:42,650 --> 00:00:47,640
[MUSIC PLAYING]

11
00:03:13,040 --> 00:03:14,000
Hello.

12
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:16,070
I'm Christa McAuliffe,
 talking to you

13
00:03:16,070 --> 00:03:19,580
from the flight deck of the
 space shuttle Challenger.

14
00:03:19,580 --> 00:03:23,530
We're in orbit now and
 we've just stowed our seats.

15
00:03:23,530 --> 00:03:26,410
Since we're weightless, we won't
 be bolting them back in again

16
00:03:26,410 --> 00:03:28,720
until our return to Earth.

17
00:03:28,720 --> 00:03:31,180
Let me tell you being
 launched into space

18
00:03:31,180 --> 00:03:34,630
is every bit as thrilling
 as they said it would be.

19
00:03:34,630 --> 00:03:37,330
When those main engines
 ignite, and right

20
00:03:37,330 --> 00:03:39,280
after them the solid
 rocket boosters

21
00:03:39,280 --> 00:03:41,800
and you're just hurled
 upwards, well, it's

22
00:03:41,800 --> 00:03:45,480
something unusual in this
 school teacher's life.

23
00:03:45,480 --> 00:03:48,510
By the time the shuttle
 reaches the top of the tower,

24
00:03:48,510 --> 00:03:50,970
you're going 100 miles an hour.

25
00:03:50,970 --> 00:03:53,250
Two minutes later,
 you're leaving the earth

26
00:03:53,250 --> 00:03:55,560
at 3,000 miles an hour.

27
00:03:55,560 --> 00:03:59,790
3,312.5.

28
00:03:59,790 --> 00:04:00,750
I knew that.

29
00:04:00,750 --> 00:04:01,800
She's within 10%.

30
00:04:01,800 --> 00:04:03,250
That's good enough
 for high school.

31
00:04:03,250 --> 00:04:04,710
Not in my class.

32
00:04:04,710 --> 00:04:05,850
I'll vouch for that.

33
00:04:05,850 --> 00:04:08,310
I watch her correct
 her homework papers.

34
00:04:08,310 --> 00:04:10,310
All right, class,
 order, order.

35
00:04:10,310 --> 00:04:11,870
Please, Christa, go on.

36
00:04:11,870 --> 00:04:14,910
Now I'd like you
 to meet our crew.

37
00:04:14,910 --> 00:04:17,460
This is the flight deck and
 on my left is our commander

38
00:04:17,460 --> 00:04:18,570
Richard Scobee.

39
00:04:18,570 --> 00:04:19,330
We call him Scobe.

40
00:04:22,820 --> 00:04:26,010
He's one of the few enlisted
 men to have become an astronaut,

41
00:04:26,010 --> 00:04:29,310
and we're very proud
 that he's our commander.

42
00:04:29,310 --> 00:04:31,690
Boy, look at those
 lovebirds holding hands.

43
00:04:31,690 --> 00:04:32,450
Frightening.

44
00:04:32,450 --> 00:04:35,240
Don't make fun of romance,
 honey, or I'll go and knock you

45
00:04:35,240 --> 00:04:38,640
upside your head,
 dear country boy.

46
00:04:38,640 --> 00:04:40,820
Well?

47
00:04:40,820 --> 00:04:42,720
Come on, let her rehearse.

48
00:04:42,720 --> 00:04:45,260
Well, who's next, Christa?

49
00:04:45,260 --> 00:04:48,920
On my right is my
 husband Stephen McAuliffe.

50
00:04:48,920 --> 00:04:53,320
He'll be-- oh, no, honey,
 you won't be on the flight.

51
00:04:53,320 --> 00:04:55,750
I'll be home doing
 the breakfast dishes.

52
00:04:55,750 --> 00:04:56,450
Wait a minute.

53
00:04:56,450 --> 00:04:58,300
Let's put some order into this.

54
00:04:58,300 --> 00:05:02,450
The man really on her right
 will be our pilot Michael Smith.

55
00:05:05,570 --> 00:05:07,680
And I'm Judy Resnick,
 the flight engineer.

56
00:05:10,860 --> 00:05:13,380
And she sits right
 behind Scobe and me

57
00:05:13,380 --> 00:05:15,300
and during the ascent phase
 and on our return to Earth,

58
00:05:15,300 --> 00:05:18,200
she watches us to make sure
 that we do everything right,

59
00:05:18,200 --> 00:05:20,180
and everybody else watches her.

60
00:05:20,180 --> 00:05:21,480
Except you, I'm sure.

61
00:05:21,480 --> 00:05:23,010
Except me, of course.

62
00:05:23,010 --> 00:05:26,400
I'm always looking
 over at you, hon.

63
00:05:26,400 --> 00:05:28,020
I'm getting to like
 this role, Christa.

64
00:05:28,020 --> 00:05:29,390
You play the flight engineer.

65
00:05:29,390 --> 00:05:31,920
Take it, JR.

66
00:05:31,920 --> 00:05:35,550
And now, from the coffee
 fields of the Kona coast,

67
00:05:35,550 --> 00:05:37,530
one of the macadamia nuts--

68
00:05:37,530 --> 00:05:40,860
And the man who still thinks
 I shouldn't be on this mission.

69
00:05:40,860 --> 00:05:41,640
That's right.

70
00:05:41,640 --> 00:05:43,440
What do you have
 against us teachers, El?

71
00:05:43,440 --> 00:05:44,880
Hey, nothing against teachers.

72
00:05:44,880 --> 00:05:47,430
Hey, wait, let
 me introduce him.

73
00:05:47,430 --> 00:05:49,970
Mission specialist,
 Ellison Onizuka.

74
00:05:53,620 --> 00:05:56,090
Come on, El, give us
 your deepest thoughts.

75
00:05:56,090 --> 00:05:58,080
You'll feel better.

76
00:05:58,080 --> 00:06:00,900
Well, we just scrubbed
 for the second time.

77
00:06:00,900 --> 00:06:01,730
Why?

78
00:06:01,730 --> 00:06:05,060
Because the shuttle is the most
 complicated machine ever built.

79
00:06:05,060 --> 00:06:07,960
You know, they call it
 operational, but it isn't.

80
00:06:07,960 --> 00:06:10,070
It's still experimental.

81
00:06:10,070 --> 00:06:13,860
I'm going whatever they
 call it, so move over, El.

82
00:06:13,860 --> 00:06:16,580
And if it's experimental,
 only professional astronauts

83
00:06:16,580 --> 00:06:19,100
should be flying it,
 which doesn't mean I

84
00:06:19,100 --> 00:06:20,780
won't enjoy going with Christa.

85
00:06:20,780 --> 00:06:21,750
What about me, El?

86
00:06:21,750 --> 00:06:23,150
Glad to be flying with me?

87
00:06:23,150 --> 00:06:25,220
Oh, no, you're too
 much of an achiever.

88
00:06:25,220 --> 00:06:27,520
You've got all these
 doctorates from MIT.

89
00:06:27,520 --> 00:06:30,290
Hey, what are you, a pineapple
 picker from Kealakekua?

90
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:34,590
All right, let's get
 back on track here.

91
00:06:34,590 --> 00:06:37,050
NASA's number one
 laser physicist,

92
00:06:37,050 --> 00:06:39,030
the man who launched
 our Spartan satellite

93
00:06:39,030 --> 00:06:40,680
to photograph Halley's comet--

94
00:06:40,680 --> 00:06:43,170
And the sweetest sax
 player this side of Mars.

95
00:06:43,170 --> 00:06:44,970
Mission specialist,
 Ron McNair.

96
00:06:48,610 --> 00:06:52,090
And don't forget, El,
 black belt in karate.

97
00:06:52,090 --> 00:06:53,050
Show him, honey.

98
00:06:53,050 --> 00:06:55,060
Kick some butt.

99
00:06:55,060 --> 00:06:57,860
And finally, from
 Hughes Aircraft,

100
00:06:57,860 --> 00:07:01,660
my fellow outsider on
 the flight, Greg Jarvis.

101
00:07:01,660 --> 00:07:02,500
That's my hero.

102
00:07:06,720 --> 00:07:10,200
All right, Christa,
 that was perfect chaos.

103
00:07:10,200 --> 00:07:11,940
Flawless, actually.

104
00:07:11,940 --> 00:07:14,640
You'll be fine when you
 do it from space tomorrow.

105
00:07:14,640 --> 00:07:16,350
I wish we didn't have
 to wait until tomorrow.

106
00:07:16,350 --> 00:07:19,670
I could go out right
 now and get on board.

107
00:07:19,670 --> 00:07:21,210
Well, I wouldn't quite yet.

108
00:07:21,210 --> 00:07:23,750
The way I see this weather, none
 of us will be flying tomorrow.

109
00:07:26,610 --> 00:07:28,820
I know everybody's
 a little frustrated.

110
00:07:28,820 --> 00:07:31,730
It's our fourth scrub
 in the last month,

111
00:07:31,730 --> 00:07:34,860
but let's work on a
 quick turnaround, huh?

112
00:07:34,860 --> 00:07:37,860
Any contractor see any change
 in their flight readiness?

113
00:07:37,860 --> 00:07:38,710
Uh-uhn.

114
00:07:38,710 --> 00:07:40,280
No.

115
00:07:40,280 --> 00:07:41,590
OK.

116
00:07:41,590 --> 00:07:47,390
Let's schedule launch for
 0938 tomorrow morning.

117
00:07:47,390 --> 00:07:51,460
Now, very important,
 extremely cold

118
00:07:51,460 --> 00:07:55,840
temperatures, into the low 20s,
 have been forecast for tonight.

119
00:07:55,840 --> 00:07:58,490
How will this
 affect each of you?

120
00:07:58,490 --> 00:07:59,340
Lockheed?

121
00:07:59,340 --> 00:08:01,230
If temperatures get
 down to the low 20s,

122
00:08:01,230 --> 00:08:02,970
we'll have a hard
 freeze for sure.

123
00:08:02,970 --> 00:08:05,250
We've never launched at
 anything close to that.

124
00:08:05,250 --> 00:08:08,000
I'll have to get more
 information, Arnie.

125
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:09,170
Rockwell?

126
00:08:09,170 --> 00:08:11,390
We need to figure these
 temperatures into our data,

127
00:08:11,390 --> 00:08:12,890
but it looks possible.

128
00:08:12,890 --> 00:08:15,090
Larry?

129
00:08:15,090 --> 00:08:17,560
Oh, I can't give
 a definite yet.

130
00:08:17,560 --> 00:08:19,030
I want to find out
 if this kind of cold

131
00:08:19,030 --> 00:08:20,590
would trigger a
 violation of the launch

132
00:08:20,590 --> 00:08:23,170
commit criteria on the
 solid rocket boosters.

133
00:08:23,170 --> 00:08:24,690
All right.

134
00:08:24,690 --> 00:08:27,690
Jesse and I will be
 in the ops center.

135
00:08:27,690 --> 00:08:31,410
Lewis, get me the firing room.

136
00:08:31,410 --> 00:08:32,110
Right.

137
00:08:32,110 --> 00:08:32,810
Right, Arnie.

138
00:08:38,960 --> 00:08:41,590
24 hour turnaround,
 go with a soft count.

139
00:08:41,590 --> 00:08:42,290
Right, Gene.

140
00:08:42,290 --> 00:08:47,720
4, 3, 2, and--

141
00:08:47,720 --> 00:08:48,850
there it goes, folks.

142
00:08:48,850 --> 00:08:50,520
Countdown has begun.

143
00:08:50,520 --> 00:08:51,940
[CHEERING]

144
00:08:59,720 --> 00:09:03,970
Wondering what it's going
 to be like up there, Christa?

145
00:09:03,970 --> 00:09:07,780
No, I was back in the past.

146
00:09:07,780 --> 00:09:11,350
Six months ago, the
 day I was chosen.

147
00:09:11,350 --> 00:09:14,420
I was a small town
 schoolteacher.

148
00:09:14,420 --> 00:09:16,750
The closest I'd ever
 been to flying anything

149
00:09:16,750 --> 00:09:20,780
was the coach section
 of an airliner.

150
00:09:20,780 --> 00:09:24,030
I never could have imagined
 that I'd be here now the night

151
00:09:24,030 --> 00:09:27,510
before a launch,
 all of us having

152
00:09:27,510 --> 00:09:30,210
become the family that we are.

153
00:09:30,210 --> 00:09:33,050
Any of you remember what
 you were doing July 19th?

154
00:09:33,050 --> 00:09:34,810
Sweating.

155
00:09:34,810 --> 00:09:38,580
That's the main thing you
 do in Houston on July 19th.

156
00:09:38,580 --> 00:09:42,430
I think Lorna was giving
 me problems on July 19th,

157
00:09:42,430 --> 00:09:45,200
but that could
 have been any day.

158
00:09:45,200 --> 00:09:46,800
What were you
 remembering, Christa?

159
00:09:46,800 --> 00:09:48,620
I'd rather hear what
 you were doing back then.

160
00:09:48,620 --> 00:09:49,840
No, we'll catch up with you.

161
00:09:49,840 --> 00:09:50,900
Come on.

162
00:09:50,900 --> 00:09:51,600
Come on.

163
00:09:54,360 --> 00:09:58,320
Well, it was an
 absolutely crazy morning.

164
00:09:58,320 --> 00:10:02,160
NASA had brought all 10 of
 us finalists to Washington,

165
00:10:02,160 --> 00:10:04,440
and the winner was
 going to be announced

166
00:10:04,440 --> 00:10:07,260
at a ceremony at
 the White House,

167
00:10:07,260 --> 00:10:09,930
but we wanted to
 know ahead of time.

168
00:10:09,930 --> 00:10:12,600
We didn't want to find out at
 the same moment as the rest

169
00:10:12,600 --> 00:10:17,020
of the country, but Ann
 Bradley was in charge

170
00:10:17,020 --> 00:10:19,580
and she absolutely
 would not tell us.

171
00:10:19,580 --> 00:10:21,720
It's out of my
 control, everyone.

172
00:10:21,720 --> 00:10:23,790
The White House will
 administer floggings

173
00:10:23,790 --> 00:10:25,140
if the winner's name leaks.

174
00:10:25,140 --> 00:10:27,940
They're acting like this is
 a national security issue.

175
00:10:27,940 --> 00:10:31,140
Ann, I think what you should
 do is call the White House

176
00:10:31,140 --> 00:10:33,900
and tell them that the teachers
 aren't coming unless we know

177
00:10:33,900 --> 00:10:35,580
in advance who the winner is.

178
00:10:35,580 --> 00:10:36,680
Yes, now you're talking.

179
00:10:36,680 --> 00:10:39,270
I think that's a great idea.

180
00:10:39,270 --> 00:10:41,580
You absolutely
 cannot tell anyone.

181
00:10:41,580 --> 00:10:42,280
OK, we got.

182
00:10:42,280 --> 00:10:43,130
I mean it.

183
00:10:43,130 --> 00:10:44,190
All right, all right.

184
00:10:44,190 --> 00:10:45,050
Come on.

185
00:10:45,050 --> 00:10:46,250
I'll tell you at
 the end of lunch.

186
00:10:49,950 --> 00:10:51,570
What do your kids think?

187
00:10:51,570 --> 00:10:53,540
My kids are a little too
 young to understand their mother

188
00:10:53,540 --> 00:10:55,400
wanting to go up into space.

189
00:10:55,400 --> 00:10:57,620
I mean, how do they explain
 that to their friends?

190
00:10:57,620 --> 00:10:59,680
Well, how's your
 husband holding up?

191
00:10:59,680 --> 00:11:00,380
It's rough.

192
00:11:00,380 --> 00:11:03,080
He says he's writing an
 article on child management

193
00:11:03,080 --> 00:11:07,140
through the massive
 use of cornflakes.

194
00:11:07,140 --> 00:11:11,390
Better tell him to stock up on
 a lot more cornflakes, Christa.

195
00:11:11,390 --> 00:11:12,290
Excuse me?

196
00:11:12,290 --> 00:11:13,580
You're going.

197
00:11:13,580 --> 00:11:15,270
You're the one
 going up in space.

198
00:11:19,220 --> 00:11:22,390
Christa, I am
 so happy for you.

199
00:11:22,390 --> 00:11:25,660
So sad for me, but--

200
00:11:25,660 --> 00:11:28,720
It's terrible we cannot be
 going up in space together.

201
00:11:28,720 --> 00:11:33,120
And Barbara Morgan
 is the alternate.

202
00:11:33,120 --> 00:11:35,140
And I might as well
 spill everything.

203
00:11:35,140 --> 00:11:38,250
The rest of you will be
 employed by NASA for a year.

204
00:11:43,450 --> 00:11:44,150
Christa.

205
00:11:47,600 --> 00:11:48,880
Do you realize?

206
00:11:48,880 --> 00:11:49,580
I don't.

207
00:11:49,580 --> 00:11:50,280
I don't.

208
00:11:50,280 --> 00:11:51,380
It just doesn't seem possible.

209
00:11:51,380 --> 00:11:55,640
You're actually
 going into space.

210
00:11:55,640 --> 00:11:56,890
You think there
 will be a recount?

211
00:11:56,890 --> 00:12:01,490
Christa, even if there were a
 recount, you'd still win again.

212
00:12:20,530 --> 00:12:24,040
It's not often that a
 teacher is at a loss for words.

213
00:12:24,040 --> 00:12:25,440
I know my students would agree.

214
00:12:28,240 --> 00:12:33,680
I've made nine wonderful
 friends in the last two weeks,

215
00:12:33,680 --> 00:12:45,950
and when that shuttle goes
 there might be one body,

216
00:12:45,950 --> 00:12:48,580
but there's going to be 10
 souls I'm taking with me.

217
00:12:48,580 --> 00:12:49,280
Thank you.

218
00:12:54,710 --> 00:12:57,120
We'll only practice
 about an hour today, Scobe.

219
00:12:57,120 --> 00:12:58,760
Why is that?

220
00:12:58,760 --> 00:13:00,450
The other aircraft
 in maintenance,

221
00:13:00,450 --> 00:13:03,470
so this one's on overload.

222
00:13:03,470 --> 00:13:06,090
Weren't you scheduled to
 get another landing trainer?

223
00:13:06,090 --> 00:13:10,370
We keep asking and
 they keep promising.

224
00:13:10,370 --> 00:13:12,270
Still looking for a
 January launch, Scobe?

225
00:13:12,270 --> 00:13:16,340
They don't change payload
 or add a congressman.

226
00:13:16,340 --> 00:13:18,710
I think I'm going to go even
 if no one else is ready.

227
00:13:18,710 --> 00:13:19,410
I agree.

228
00:13:19,410 --> 00:13:20,810
You're ready for a real one.

229
00:13:37,690 --> 00:13:38,910
What number is this?

230
00:13:38,910 --> 00:13:39,750
You got it there?

231
00:13:39,750 --> 00:13:41,330
Yes, sir.

232
00:13:41,330 --> 00:13:43,050
You're getting close
 to your 900th shuttle

233
00:13:43,050 --> 00:13:44,700
landing rehearsal, Commander.

234
00:13:44,700 --> 00:13:46,890
It's OK, Scobe, you'll get
 the hang of it pretty soon.

235
00:13:46,890 --> 00:13:48,360
Yeah, well, I hope so.

236
00:13:48,360 --> 00:13:50,880
The folks with me are going
 to be real interested in how

237
00:13:50,880 --> 00:13:52,220
I fly the shuttle.

238
00:13:52,220 --> 00:13:55,840
Hey, that's right,
 you got the teacher.

239
00:13:55,840 --> 00:13:57,100
How'd you find that out?

240
00:13:57,100 --> 00:13:58,740
We just heard.

241
00:13:58,740 --> 00:14:00,470
They tell the
 important people first.

242
00:14:00,470 --> 00:14:01,920
That a good idea, Scobe?

243
00:14:01,920 --> 00:14:04,620
You like the idea of an outsider
 getting a seat on your shuttle?

244
00:14:07,210 --> 00:14:10,360
Well, it torqued me at first.

245
00:14:10,360 --> 00:14:12,730
You know, we got guys in this
 program who were waiting 15

246
00:14:12,730 --> 00:14:14,730
years to fly and then they
 lose their seat to somebody who

247
00:14:14,730 --> 00:14:17,280
just walks in off the street.

248
00:14:17,280 --> 00:14:18,610
But I liked the
 idea of us sending

249
00:14:18,610 --> 00:14:20,920
the first lesson from space.

250
00:14:20,920 --> 00:14:22,210
I think a lot of
 it'll depend on what

251
00:14:22,210 --> 00:14:24,810
this Christa person is like.

252
00:14:24,810 --> 00:14:26,320
All right, let's
 fly the shuttle.

253
00:14:31,750 --> 00:14:33,340
Yours, Scobe.

254
00:14:33,340 --> 00:14:34,590
Well, what do I do first?

255
00:14:34,590 --> 00:14:35,290
Pull this?

256
00:14:51,190 --> 00:14:52,480
You're off line.

257
00:14:52,480 --> 00:14:53,180
Right.

258
00:14:53,180 --> 00:14:54,180
I see it.

259
00:15:46,860 --> 00:15:50,430
Scobe, one thing, if you
 break through cloud cover,

260
00:15:50,430 --> 00:15:52,980
you're 7,000 feet, and
 you're off line that far,

261
00:15:52,980 --> 00:15:54,790
better jump on it even quicker.

262
00:15:54,790 --> 00:15:56,480
You need to correct
 it right now.

263
00:15:56,480 --> 00:15:57,180
Right.

264
00:15:57,180 --> 00:15:58,180
I can do better.

265
00:15:58,180 --> 00:15:59,670
Watch this next one.

266
00:16:35,480 --> 00:16:38,060
How soon can we get inside
 and take a look at the O-rings?

267
00:16:38,060 --> 00:16:39,290
We start taking
 it apart tomorrow.

268
00:16:39,290 --> 00:16:41,160
In a couple of days, we'll
 give you everything you want.

269
00:16:45,290 --> 00:16:48,560
These horizontal tests
 don't give us what we want.

270
00:16:48,560 --> 00:16:50,330
The only thing that will
 give us real information

271
00:16:50,330 --> 00:16:53,350
is the vertical firing
 under flight conditions.

272
00:16:53,350 --> 00:16:54,890
We fire it the way
 we're told to, Roger.

273
00:16:54,890 --> 00:16:56,030
We know that, Stan.

274
00:16:56,030 --> 00:16:57,910
If we try to test one of
 these things vertically,

275
00:16:57,910 --> 00:16:59,610
there's no way to hold it down.
 It'll launch itself.

276
00:16:59,610 --> 00:17:00,310
Fine.

277
00:17:00,310 --> 00:17:02,000
But the only way to know
 exactly what we've got

278
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:03,820
is with a vertical firing.

279
00:17:03,820 --> 00:17:05,600
Somebody ought to
 tell management that.

280
00:17:05,600 --> 00:17:07,450
Well, we can't tell
 nothing to nobody today.

281
00:17:07,450 --> 00:17:08,150
It's quitting time.

282
00:17:08,150 --> 00:17:09,080
How about a beer?

283
00:17:09,080 --> 00:17:10,550
We don't drink in my family.

284
00:17:10,550 --> 00:17:11,330
OK.

285
00:17:11,330 --> 00:17:13,100
Come on over the bowling
 alley, knock down some pins.

286
00:17:13,100 --> 00:17:14,190
It'll make you feel mighty.

287
00:17:14,190 --> 00:17:16,880
See you in a couple of days.

288
00:17:16,880 --> 00:17:18,230
Typical.

289
00:17:18,230 --> 00:17:20,160
Nobody seems to take
 this problem seriously.

290
00:17:20,160 --> 00:17:22,920
I'll bet 90% of the people
 who work here don't even know

291
00:17:22,920 --> 00:17:25,040
what an O-ring is, let
 alone there's a serious

292
00:17:25,040 --> 00:17:26,630
problem with them.

293
00:17:26,630 --> 00:17:27,930
Real discouraging.

294
00:17:27,930 --> 00:17:29,870
What's discouraging
 is Morton-Thiokol

295
00:17:29,870 --> 00:17:31,940
not getting off its behind
 and doing something about it.

296
00:17:31,940 --> 00:17:32,640
Right.

297
00:17:32,640 --> 00:17:36,320
They met their contract with
 NASA, the shuttle is flying,

298
00:17:36,320 --> 00:17:38,690
why talk about problems
 is their attitude.

299
00:17:38,690 --> 00:17:40,130
They'll have to
 talk about this one.

300
00:17:40,130 --> 00:17:42,400
I hear if this O-ring
 problem isn't solved soon,

301
00:17:42,400 --> 00:17:44,660
NASA will be looking
 for another contractor.

302
00:17:44,660 --> 00:17:45,920
No way.

303
00:17:45,920 --> 00:17:48,380
If NASA dropped
 Morton-Thiokol, they'd

304
00:17:48,380 --> 00:17:50,360
had to suspend the shuttle
 program for a year,

305
00:17:50,360 --> 00:17:54,650
redesign the entire booster,
 start a whole new test program.

306
00:17:54,650 --> 00:17:57,790
You know that's not
 going to happen.

307
00:17:57,790 --> 00:17:59,690
Ichi.

308
00:17:59,690 --> 00:18:01,460
Ni.

309
00:18:01,460 --> 00:18:03,420
San.

310
00:18:03,420 --> 00:18:04,760
Shi.

311
00:18:04,760 --> 00:18:06,980
Ichi.

312
00:18:06,980 --> 00:18:08,430
Ni.

313
00:18:08,430 --> 00:18:10,310
San.

314
00:18:10,310 --> 00:18:12,370
Shi.

315
00:18:12,370 --> 00:18:13,510
Ichi.

316
00:18:13,510 --> 00:18:14,210
Ni.

317
00:18:16,620 --> 00:18:17,320
Yame.

318
00:18:21,130 --> 00:18:21,830
Rei.

319
00:18:25,840 --> 00:18:26,540
Seiza.

320
00:18:32,590 --> 00:18:36,060
Do you study karate
 to fight others?

321
00:18:36,060 --> 00:18:38,010
Charlie?

322
00:18:38,010 --> 00:18:41,190
I study karate to improve
 myself through self-discipline

323
00:18:41,190 --> 00:18:44,160
and self-criticism, to
 learn to overcome failure,

324
00:18:44,160 --> 00:18:48,160
hardship, and fear.

325
00:18:48,160 --> 00:18:52,160
For what other purpose
 do you learn karate?

326
00:18:52,160 --> 00:18:54,620
Al?

327
00:18:54,620 --> 00:18:56,410
To know courage and beauty.

328
00:18:56,410 --> 00:18:58,100
Through karate,
 the warrior finds

329
00:18:58,100 --> 00:19:00,960
the beauty that lies
 in a lily, in music,

330
00:19:00,960 --> 00:19:02,540
and the knowledge of
 what he might become.

331
00:19:08,210 --> 00:19:11,040
Is this a moment in
 which to fight or to smile?

332
00:19:15,310 --> 00:19:17,210
OK.

333
00:19:17,210 --> 00:19:18,450
See you Thursday.

334
00:19:18,450 --> 00:19:19,430
Ha, Sensai.

335
00:19:31,150 --> 00:19:31,850
Sensai?

336
00:19:31,850 --> 00:19:32,550
Hm?

337
00:19:32,550 --> 00:19:33,720
Did you hear
 you're going to have

338
00:19:33,720 --> 00:19:34,780
that teacher on your shuttle?

339
00:19:34,780 --> 00:19:35,860
I did. yes.

340
00:19:35,860 --> 00:19:37,240
What's that going to be like?

341
00:19:37,240 --> 00:19:39,430
I mean, you're this brain
 already been in space, ans

342
00:19:39,430 --> 00:19:40,990
she's a high school teacher.

343
00:19:40,990 --> 00:19:42,370
Who's going to be teaching who?

344
00:19:42,370 --> 00:19:43,880
Well, that's not the question.

345
00:19:43,880 --> 00:19:46,390
The question is, where's
 the opportunity here?

346
00:19:46,390 --> 00:19:50,050
I knew he was going
 to turn his back on me.

347
00:19:50,050 --> 00:19:51,720
Why is she you
 going into space?

348
00:19:51,720 --> 00:19:54,380
And who'll be listening
 when she's teaching?

349
00:19:54,380 --> 00:19:55,660
Calvin?

350
00:19:55,660 --> 00:19:56,440
Us?

351
00:19:56,440 --> 00:19:57,280
Us.

352
00:19:57,280 --> 00:19:58,550
When the teacher is
 giving her lesson,

353
00:19:58,550 --> 00:20:00,010
I'll be staring down
 into your classroom

354
00:20:00,010 --> 00:20:01,710
to see if you are listening.

355
00:20:01,710 --> 00:20:02,410
Hm?

356
00:20:12,100 --> 00:20:14,870
Hey, Roger, have
 you got a minute?

357
00:20:14,870 --> 00:20:17,500
Come on over.

358
00:20:17,500 --> 00:20:21,510
I hear you've had a
 couple of new thoughts.

359
00:20:21,510 --> 00:20:23,490
Yes, I do.

360
00:20:23,490 --> 00:20:25,820
I wrote a memo to
 Bob Lund about it.

361
00:20:25,820 --> 00:20:26,820
Well, what's the meat of it?

362
00:20:26,820 --> 00:20:28,110
Would you mind telling us?

363
00:20:28,110 --> 00:20:30,870
Well, I think we've had
 a mistake in position.

364
00:20:30,870 --> 00:20:33,810
We believe we can get a new
 design going for the O-ring

365
00:20:33,810 --> 00:20:37,140
and continue to fly
 without any real worry.

366
00:20:37,140 --> 00:20:38,360
So what's changed?

367
00:20:38,360 --> 00:20:40,410
We're working on the new design.

368
00:20:40,410 --> 00:20:42,220
We sure as hell
 have to keep flying.

369
00:20:42,220 --> 00:20:44,310
NASA's nearly doubled the
 schedule for next year.

370
00:20:44,310 --> 00:20:46,400
I don't think we have to fly.

371
00:20:46,400 --> 00:20:48,030
I mean, we're sending
 those shuttles up like they

372
00:20:48,030 --> 00:20:50,430
can't fail or something.

373
00:20:50,430 --> 00:20:52,470
It's a different
 ballgame since flight 17.

374
00:20:52,470 --> 00:20:54,440
I don't see it as
 a different ballgame.

375
00:20:54,440 --> 00:20:56,610
There's a problem,
 and we got to fix it.

376
00:20:56,610 --> 00:20:58,740
Isn't that what
 you're saying, Roger?

377
00:20:58,740 --> 00:21:01,870
I'm saying that and I'm
 saying something else too.

378
00:21:01,870 --> 00:21:03,840
Oh, come on, you have
 to play this for drama?

379
00:21:03,840 --> 00:21:05,910
Just say what you got to say.

380
00:21:05,910 --> 00:21:07,470
Since flight 17,
 we know something

381
00:21:07,470 --> 00:21:09,430
we didn't know before.

382
00:21:09,430 --> 00:21:12,150
The primary O-ring
 can fail completely.

383
00:21:12,150 --> 00:21:14,890
If that ever happens, one of the
 major sections to the rocket,

384
00:21:14,890 --> 00:21:18,690
it's a jump ball as to whether
 the joint holds or fails.

385
00:21:18,690 --> 00:21:21,330
If it fails, it'll
 be a catastrophe

386
00:21:21,330 --> 00:21:23,220
of the highest order.

387
00:21:23,220 --> 00:21:25,230
Loss of human life.

388
00:21:25,230 --> 00:21:27,030
The shuttle, the
 launch pad, all of it.

389
00:21:30,200 --> 00:21:31,760
Roger, you're keyed
 up about the O-ring

390
00:21:31,760 --> 00:21:33,680
problem because O-rings
 is what you work on.

391
00:21:33,680 --> 00:21:36,050
It's what you see every day.

392
00:21:36,050 --> 00:21:38,390
I want you to know there
 are other major problems

393
00:21:38,390 --> 00:21:43,130
on the shuttle, cracks in the
 blades of the main engines,

394
00:21:43,130 --> 00:21:45,050
brakes, computer malfunctions.

395
00:21:45,050 --> 00:21:46,790
If any one of these
 fail, it could

396
00:21:46,790 --> 00:21:50,400
bring the same devastation
 you're talking about.

397
00:21:50,400 --> 00:21:51,800
Now, we've got to fix
 this O-ring problem.

398
00:21:51,800 --> 00:21:56,090
There's no question
 about that, but, Roger,

399
00:21:56,090 --> 00:22:01,760
the shuttle has flown 19 times
 and it's come back 19 times.

400
00:22:01,760 --> 00:22:03,650
Our job isn't to run
 around like Chicken Little

401
00:22:03,650 --> 00:22:05,740
hollering the sky is falling.

402
00:22:05,740 --> 00:22:07,100
It's to fix this
 problem, and when

403
00:22:07,100 --> 00:22:09,080
the next problem
 comes up fix that,

404
00:22:09,080 --> 00:22:10,580
and keep that shuttle flying.

405
00:22:26,490 --> 00:22:28,590
Do you remember Claire?

406
00:22:28,590 --> 00:22:31,280
Um, yeah, read hair.

407
00:22:31,280 --> 00:22:31,980
Right.

408
00:22:31,980 --> 00:22:33,470
We saw her at the PTA meeting.

409
00:22:33,470 --> 00:22:34,170
Uh-huh.

410
00:22:34,870 --> 00:22:36,190
Well, her husband's
 this race nut

411
00:22:36,190 --> 00:22:38,460
and he has a soundtrack
 of cars screaming

412
00:22:38,460 --> 00:22:39,720
around the Indy track.

413
00:22:39,720 --> 00:22:40,600
Yeah.

414
00:22:40,600 --> 00:22:41,800
I'm going to play
 it as background

415
00:22:41,800 --> 00:22:43,550
for your morning preparations.

416
00:22:43,550 --> 00:22:44,250
Uh-huh.

417
00:22:44,250 --> 00:22:45,760
Oh, very funny, hon.

418
00:22:45,760 --> 00:22:49,810
We're overload today On
 Scobee's going to Washington.

419
00:22:49,810 --> 00:22:53,350
I've got to fly to the Cape to
 check out the escape system,

420
00:22:53,350 --> 00:22:56,000
then get back for the
 seminar on fire control

421
00:22:56,000 --> 00:22:57,870
that we're having
 here this afternoon,

422
00:22:57,870 --> 00:23:00,010
and I've still got to bone
 up for the standalone seminar

423
00:23:00,010 --> 00:23:01,240
that we're having Wednesday.

424
00:23:01,240 --> 00:23:02,830
Well, there's only one way.

425
00:23:02,830 --> 00:23:03,730
Plan the work--

426
00:23:03,730 --> 00:23:04,970
And work the plan.

427
00:23:04,970 --> 00:23:06,470
Otherwise it will
 never get done.

428
00:23:06,470 --> 00:23:07,750
Right.

429
00:23:07,750 --> 00:23:10,270
Talking of plan and
 work, do you think we

430
00:23:10,270 --> 00:23:12,080
could work in some family time?

431
00:23:12,080 --> 00:23:14,150
Yeah, we have to.

432
00:23:14,150 --> 00:23:14,920
When?

433
00:23:14,920 --> 00:23:15,620
I don't know.

434
00:23:15,620 --> 00:23:16,390
You tell me.

435
00:23:16,390 --> 00:23:17,090
Saturday?

436
00:23:20,710 --> 00:23:23,960
40 minutes right after lunch,
 I could probably do that.

437
00:23:23,960 --> 00:23:26,470
A full 40 minutes?

438
00:23:26,470 --> 00:23:28,030
Oh my.

439
00:23:28,030 --> 00:23:31,060
I didn't dare hope we'd
 get that kind of time.

440
00:23:31,060 --> 00:23:34,990
Hon, I know, it's just
 that there are so many things

441
00:23:34,990 --> 00:23:35,860
that I've got to get done.

442
00:23:41,210 --> 00:23:43,840
Come on, let's say
 goodbye to the kids.

443
00:23:43,840 --> 00:23:45,220
When will you be back, Dad?

444
00:23:45,220 --> 00:23:46,030
Saturday.

445
00:23:46,030 --> 00:23:47,950
Right in time for
 Janelle's soccer game.

446
00:23:47,950 --> 00:23:50,560
You missed the
 last one, so be sure.

447
00:23:50,560 --> 00:23:52,340
You won't be back in time, El.

448
00:23:52,340 --> 00:23:53,040
Why?

449
00:23:53,040 --> 00:23:53,740
Why?

450
00:23:53,740 --> 00:23:55,180
When you go to the
 Cape you get back late.

451
00:23:55,180 --> 00:23:56,290
Sometimes.

452
00:23:56,290 --> 00:23:57,370
Usually.

453
00:23:57,370 --> 00:23:59,080
Hey, if I don't get here,
 it's because something

454
00:23:59,080 --> 00:24:00,340
made it impossible.

455
00:24:00,340 --> 00:24:01,710
I'll get here as soon as I can.

456
00:24:01,710 --> 00:24:03,370
And mostly, it's when
 we're already asleep

457
00:24:03,370 --> 00:24:04,960
and then you're gone
 before we get up.

458
00:24:04,960 --> 00:24:08,470
We know you've been here
 by the laundry you leave.

459
00:24:08,470 --> 00:24:10,390
Try to get here, Dad.

460
00:24:10,390 --> 00:24:12,300
I need help with my algebra too.

461
00:24:12,300 --> 00:24:14,210
I'll be here.

462
00:24:14,210 --> 00:24:15,880
We'll do algebra right
 after the game, OK?

463
00:24:15,880 --> 00:24:18,800
OK.

464
00:24:18,800 --> 00:24:21,230
Now keep my record
 of punctuality perfect,

465
00:24:21,230 --> 00:24:24,370
I lift a tiny Hawaiian
 body out of here.

466
00:24:24,370 --> 00:24:25,070
Aloha.

467
00:24:43,090 --> 00:24:44,700
Well, there's no
 mystery about who you are.

468
00:24:44,700 --> 00:24:45,400
Or you.

469
00:24:45,400 --> 00:24:46,810
I've seen your picture.

470
00:24:46,810 --> 00:24:48,610
Dick Scobee.

471
00:24:48,610 --> 00:24:50,420
Quick, what's 9 times 7?

472
00:24:50,420 --> 00:24:52,080
68.

473
00:24:52,080 --> 00:24:53,500
Well, that's within 10%.

474
00:24:53,500 --> 00:24:55,060
I think that's close
 enough, don't you?

475
00:24:55,060 --> 00:24:57,520
Not in my class.

476
00:24:57,520 --> 00:24:58,910
Please, nice to meet you.

477
00:24:58,910 --> 00:24:59,610
Please sit up.

478
00:25:05,350 --> 00:25:08,350
So NASA asked me to meet
 with y'all and tell you

479
00:25:08,350 --> 00:25:10,810
something about the shuttle.

480
00:25:10,810 --> 00:25:12,010
Who's got the first question?

481
00:25:12,010 --> 00:25:12,710
I do.

482
00:25:12,710 --> 00:25:13,420
Go ahead.

483
00:25:13,420 --> 00:25:14,710
What do we call you?

484
00:25:14,710 --> 00:25:18,940
Well, Dick is fine, but
 mostly people call me Scobe.

485
00:25:18,940 --> 00:25:21,010
I picked that up
 in grammar school.

486
00:25:21,010 --> 00:25:22,120
Commander?

487
00:25:22,120 --> 00:25:24,730
Commander, no, you wouldn't
 use except during a mission,

488
00:25:24,730 --> 00:25:26,530
and even then,
 we're more informal

489
00:25:26,530 --> 00:25:27,940
unless there's a crisis.

490
00:25:27,940 --> 00:25:29,860
Not that it fixes a
 crisis that people

491
00:25:29,860 --> 00:25:32,950
start calling me commander.

492
00:25:32,950 --> 00:25:35,830
How often is there
 likely to be a crisis?

493
00:25:35,830 --> 00:25:40,250
Well, they don't appear
 on schedule, of course.

494
00:25:40,250 --> 00:25:44,450
Most of them occur during ascent
 and when we come back to Earth,

495
00:25:44,450 --> 00:25:48,220
so that's why we
 practice those the most.

496
00:25:48,220 --> 00:25:50,750
How are you in a
 crisis, Christa?

497
00:25:50,750 --> 00:25:52,800
All right, I think.

498
00:25:52,800 --> 00:25:55,710
High school teachers have all
 kinds of crises to deal with.

499
00:25:58,830 --> 00:26:02,160
How do you get to be
 commander of a shuttle?

500
00:26:02,160 --> 00:26:03,930
I mean, I guess these are
 pretty primitive questions,

501
00:26:03,930 --> 00:26:06,380
but we're just getting into
 this massive world, you know.

502
00:26:06,380 --> 00:26:07,080
No, no.

503
00:26:07,080 --> 00:26:08,100
That's fine.

504
00:26:08,100 --> 00:26:10,110
Most of us were test pilots.

505
00:26:10,110 --> 00:26:11,110
Weren't you in the military?

506
00:26:11,110 --> 00:26:11,810
Air Force.

507
00:26:11,810 --> 00:26:16,610
23 years ago, I was an
 enlisted man in San Antonio

508
00:26:16,610 --> 00:26:20,430
fixing piston engines on C124s.

509
00:26:20,430 --> 00:26:23,280
How did you get
 from there to here?

510
00:26:23,280 --> 00:26:27,300
Well, I guess I must have
 married the right woman.

511
00:26:27,300 --> 00:26:30,180
June and I, my wife
 and I, we both decided

512
00:26:30,180 --> 00:26:32,490
there was more to life
 than me fixing engines

513
00:26:32,490 --> 00:26:35,560
and her being a waitress,
 so we entered college.

514
00:26:35,560 --> 00:26:37,500
I graduated from the
 University of Arizona

515
00:26:37,500 --> 00:26:39,880
and went into pilot training.

516
00:26:39,880 --> 00:26:41,660
And June?

517
00:26:41,660 --> 00:26:44,140
Oh, I think y'all
 have a friend in June.

518
00:26:44,140 --> 00:26:48,040
She's now an assistant professor
 at the University of Houston.

519
00:26:48,040 --> 00:26:49,990
Great story.

520
00:26:49,990 --> 00:26:52,780
There's something
 that I'd like to know.

521
00:26:52,780 --> 00:26:56,790
Do you ever get scared
 flying into space?

522
00:26:56,790 --> 00:26:57,540
No.

523
00:26:57,540 --> 00:26:58,820
No, not scared.

524
00:26:58,820 --> 00:27:02,500
We've all been fighting
 too hard to get up there.

525
00:27:02,500 --> 00:27:04,960
By the time you become a
 commander of a shuttle mission,

526
00:27:04,960 --> 00:27:07,390
you've been in the
 program about eight years

527
00:27:07,390 --> 00:27:11,230
and you've done over 2,000 hours
 in the sims, in the simulators,

528
00:27:11,230 --> 00:27:15,960
so during a mission, you're
 not afraid for your life,

529
00:27:15,960 --> 00:27:18,810
you're just afraid
 of screwing up.

530
00:27:18,810 --> 00:27:21,540
Senator Garn said he
 felt safer flying in space

531
00:27:21,540 --> 00:27:23,820
than he did going down
 the George Washington

532
00:27:23,820 --> 00:27:26,790
Parkway at rush hour.

533
00:27:26,790 --> 00:27:28,800
Well, he wouldn't be.

534
00:27:28,800 --> 00:27:30,750
Flying the shuttle
 involves real danger.

535
00:27:33,740 --> 00:27:37,850
You're sitting on top of a
 controlled explosion at launch.

536
00:27:37,850 --> 00:27:41,750
Solid rockets generate
 44 million horsepower,

537
00:27:41,750 --> 00:27:46,910
and each one contains 500
 tons of explosive fuel.

538
00:27:46,910 --> 00:27:48,260
So you light them
 and you ride them

539
00:27:48,260 --> 00:27:50,240
until they burn out two
 minutes later, because there

540
00:27:50,240 --> 00:27:54,080
is no way to shut it down.

541
00:27:54,080 --> 00:27:58,040
It would be very easy for
 something to go wrong.

542
00:27:58,040 --> 00:28:00,190
And yet, you're not scared?

543
00:28:00,190 --> 00:28:06,390
And even after what you've
 just told us, neither am I.

544
00:28:06,390 --> 00:28:08,590
That's the way you have to
 feel when you're an astronaut.

545
00:28:17,770 --> 00:28:18,720
Morning, everybody.

546
00:28:18,720 --> 00:28:19,420
Morning.

547
00:28:19,420 --> 00:28:23,800
Let me remind you, this
 is a level one meeting.

548
00:28:23,800 --> 00:28:26,260
We're going to be deciding on a
 couple of very critical issues

549
00:28:26,260 --> 00:28:29,050
here today, and I put
 the O-ring problem right

550
00:28:29,050 --> 00:28:31,330
at the top of those issues.

551
00:28:31,330 --> 00:28:34,890
Larry Mulloy will begin.

552
00:28:34,890 --> 00:28:38,710
We've got a hard
 question to answer today.

553
00:28:38,710 --> 00:28:41,690
Is it safe to continue
 flying the shuttle?

554
00:28:41,690 --> 00:28:46,240
Now, if quit should be said,
 this is the time to say it.

555
00:28:46,240 --> 00:28:48,560
In the original design of
 the solid rocket booster,

556
00:28:48,560 --> 00:28:51,500
no erosion of O-rings
 was ever anticipated.

557
00:28:51,500 --> 00:28:55,760
No such possibility was
 ever even mentioned.

558
00:28:55,760 --> 00:28:59,170
O-ring erosion occurred in the
 second flight of the shuttle.

559
00:28:59,170 --> 00:29:02,510
Now we didn't know how
 serious a problem it was.

560
00:29:02,510 --> 00:29:05,720
We decided since every O-ring
 in the solid rocket booster

561
00:29:05,720 --> 00:29:10,790
has a backup, a secondary
 O-ring, safety was guaranteed.

562
00:29:10,790 --> 00:29:13,280
We decided that we would
 continue to fly the shuttle,

563
00:29:13,280 --> 00:29:16,680
but we would monitor the
 O-rings very closely.

564
00:29:16,680 --> 00:29:19,640
Now since flight 2, there
 have been continuing

565
00:29:19,640 --> 00:29:22,780
instances of O-ring erosion.

566
00:29:22,780 --> 00:29:25,480
None, however, has been greater
 than that experienced on flight

567
00:29:25,480 --> 00:29:28,720
2 so the rationale
 has become as long

568
00:29:28,720 --> 00:29:31,810
as the O-ring erosion does
 not exceed that of flight 2,

569
00:29:31,810 --> 00:29:35,260
it's safe to fly.

570
00:29:35,260 --> 00:29:38,140
But two months ago, post
 flight inspection of flight 17

571
00:29:38,140 --> 00:29:40,570
showed a brand new
 set of circumstances.

572
00:29:40,570 --> 00:29:43,570
An O-ring in a nozzle
 joint was so badly eroded,

573
00:29:43,570 --> 00:29:45,310
it didn't seal at all.

574
00:29:45,310 --> 00:29:49,990
The secondary O-ring did seal,
 but it too was badly eroded.

575
00:29:49,990 --> 00:29:51,670
Now this combination
 of erosion has

576
00:29:51,670 --> 00:29:54,330
destroyed our rationale that
 we have a guarantee of safety.

577
00:29:56,940 --> 00:29:59,430
I think that's a
 pretty fair description.

578
00:29:59,430 --> 00:30:01,690
Everybody agreed?

579
00:30:01,690 --> 00:30:02,630
Um?

580
00:30:02,630 --> 00:30:04,470
Yeah, Joe.

581
00:30:04,470 --> 00:30:06,270
Well, it was our
 engineers obviously

582
00:30:06,270 --> 00:30:11,260
who did the post flight analysis
 on 17 and produced these facts.

583
00:30:11,260 --> 00:30:13,510
No one is more concerned
 than us at Morton-Thiokol

584
00:30:13,510 --> 00:30:14,590
about what they mean.

585
00:30:14,590 --> 00:30:16,290
What do they mean?

586
00:30:16,290 --> 00:30:18,800
Well, let me say first off
 that I would be lying to you

587
00:30:18,800 --> 00:30:20,690
if I told you we know
 everything about what

588
00:30:20,690 --> 00:30:21,980
went wrong on flight 17.

589
00:30:21,980 --> 00:30:25,580
Let me tell you that's
 exactly what we've got to know.

590
00:30:25,580 --> 00:30:28,310
Everything about what did
 go wrong on flight 17,

591
00:30:28,310 --> 00:30:30,290
otherwise we don't have
 an answer to our question.

592
00:30:30,290 --> 00:30:33,170
But we do have an answer,
 Larry, continue flying.

593
00:30:33,170 --> 00:30:35,870
That's our recommendation.

594
00:30:35,870 --> 00:30:38,180
We've discovered that the
 nozzle joint was not properly

595
00:30:38,180 --> 00:30:41,360
leak checked, and because
 of that very serious mistake

596
00:30:41,360 --> 00:30:44,720
both O-rings were made
 vulnerable to the hot gases.

597
00:30:44,720 --> 00:30:47,900
We're making sure that no
 such aberration happens again,

598
00:30:47,900 --> 00:30:50,720
but we believe that that
 was the cause of the erosion

599
00:30:50,720 --> 00:30:52,310
in both O-rings on flight 17.

600
00:30:52,310 --> 00:30:54,320
And that's why we
 recommend continue

601
00:30:54,320 --> 00:30:56,180
flying with proper checks.

602
00:30:56,180 --> 00:30:58,490
Assuming what you say is
 true, that would explain

603
00:30:58,490 --> 00:31:00,050
what happened on flight 17.

604
00:31:00,050 --> 00:31:03,500
It does not explain the whole
 history of O-ring erosions.

605
00:31:03,500 --> 00:31:06,470
Improperly leak checks
 didn't cause all of them.

606
00:31:06,470 --> 00:31:09,510
O-ring erosions were
 not supposed to occur,

607
00:31:09,510 --> 00:31:12,380
but they did, and then
 sometimes they didn't.

608
00:31:12,380 --> 00:31:13,700
Why?

609
00:31:13,700 --> 00:31:15,530
I keep thinking we're
 flying rocket boosters

610
00:31:15,530 --> 00:31:17,790
we don't really understand.

611
00:31:17,790 --> 00:31:19,610
We are forming an
 O-ring task force

612
00:31:19,610 --> 00:31:22,800
at Morton-Thiokol to find
 out exactly what the problem

613
00:31:22,800 --> 00:31:25,020
is and how to fix it.

614
00:31:25,020 --> 00:31:27,810
This task force will recommend
 short and long range solutions

615
00:31:27,810 --> 00:31:29,190
to the O-ring problem.

616
00:31:29,190 --> 00:31:33,340
It's a little late in
 coming, but it's a good idea.

617
00:31:33,340 --> 00:31:35,720
It's a real good idea, Larry.

618
00:31:35,720 --> 00:31:37,860
We'll wrestle this
 thing to earth.

619
00:31:37,860 --> 00:31:39,330
All right, but
 there are conditions.

620
00:31:39,330 --> 00:31:42,540
You form that task force
 immediately and get a report

621
00:31:42,540 --> 00:31:43,770
into me within two months.

622
00:31:43,770 --> 00:31:44,740
You've got it.

623
00:31:44,740 --> 00:31:48,030
The task force begins tomorrow.

624
00:31:48,030 --> 00:31:49,450
We going right
 to meet the crew?

625
00:31:49,450 --> 00:31:51,750
That building over there.

626
00:31:51,750 --> 00:31:55,210
Barbara, why do I
 suddenly feel so inadequate?

627
00:31:55,210 --> 00:31:56,560
Because I am.

628
00:31:56,560 --> 00:31:58,150
I doubt that.

629
00:31:58,150 --> 00:32:01,250
They don't expect us
 to be brilliant yet.

630
00:32:01,250 --> 00:32:04,000
I look around here and I
 realize how little I know

631
00:32:04,000 --> 00:32:06,830
about rockets and space travel.

632
00:32:06,830 --> 00:32:11,740
I say the words, space
 travel, and I think

633
00:32:11,740 --> 00:32:13,690
is that me I'm talking about.

634
00:32:13,690 --> 00:32:14,680
You're right.

635
00:32:14,680 --> 00:32:17,480
It's intimidating.

636
00:32:17,480 --> 00:32:19,480
Now, ladies, the crew's
 very busy on some highly

637
00:32:19,480 --> 00:32:22,390
technical work, so we'll
 just sort of tiptoe in, OK?

638
00:32:22,390 --> 00:32:24,930
Just try not to
 disturb anything.

639
00:32:24,930 --> 00:32:26,160
Is it all right to go in?

640
00:32:26,160 --> 00:32:26,860
Should we wait?

641
00:32:26,860 --> 00:32:27,560
It'll be all right.

642
00:32:36,290 --> 00:32:38,320
Hi.

643
00:32:38,320 --> 00:32:39,820
I'm Elon Onizuka.

644
00:32:39,820 --> 00:32:42,130
We'd like to welcome
 our journalist in space.

645
00:32:42,130 --> 00:32:44,300
Teacher in space, fool.

646
00:32:44,300 --> 00:32:45,110
Morning, Christa.

647
00:32:45,110 --> 00:32:46,840
I'm the well-behaved
 one, Mike Smith.

648
00:32:46,840 --> 00:32:48,730
Uh, that is not the truth.

649
00:32:48,730 --> 00:32:50,560
He's always late to
 class, he doesn't

650
00:32:50,560 --> 00:32:52,360
complete his
 homework assignments,

651
00:32:52,360 --> 00:32:54,010
and he uses bad words.

652
00:32:54,010 --> 00:32:56,090
I'm the good
 student, Ron McNair.

653
00:32:56,090 --> 00:32:57,970
They're all truants, Christa.

654
00:32:57,970 --> 00:33:00,130
You and I will have to take
 this bunch of dead end kids

655
00:33:00,130 --> 00:33:01,040
on together.

656
00:33:01,040 --> 00:33:01,930
I'm Judy Resnick.

657
00:33:01,930 --> 00:33:02,630
Hi.

658
00:33:02,630 --> 00:33:04,570
I see you in all
 the best places.

659
00:33:04,570 --> 00:33:05,650
Welcome aboard, Christa.

660
00:33:05,650 --> 00:33:06,970
Thank you.

661
00:33:06,970 --> 00:33:08,860
All together now.

662
00:33:08,860 --> 00:33:10,900
Good morning, Mrs. McAuliffe.

663
00:33:14,110 --> 00:33:16,420
Good morning, class.

664
00:33:16,420 --> 00:33:17,450
Teacher, can you tell me--

665
00:33:17,450 --> 00:33:19,070
What's the capital of France?

666
00:33:19,070 --> 00:33:22,530
How high is--

667
00:33:22,530 --> 00:33:23,970
What are the primary colors?

668
00:33:23,970 --> 00:33:26,560
Ready to buy
 some beers tonight?

669
00:33:26,560 --> 00:33:28,050
No way.

670
00:33:28,050 --> 00:33:29,060
Are we about ready, Jerry?

671
00:33:29,060 --> 00:33:29,760
Pretty much.

672
00:33:29,760 --> 00:33:31,480
Got some good
 work down for us?

673
00:33:31,480 --> 00:33:33,000
You won't sleep through it.

674
00:33:33,000 --> 00:33:34,870
I want to be told
 it Mike eats a donut.

675
00:33:34,870 --> 00:33:36,010
We've got $100 bet.

676
00:33:36,010 --> 00:33:37,740
Which I've practically won.

677
00:33:37,740 --> 00:33:38,440
You wish.

678
00:33:39,850 --> 00:33:41,060
We're going to be tough today.

679
00:33:41,060 --> 00:33:43,130
You win a beer, you'll earn it.

680
00:33:43,130 --> 00:33:44,860
Better get your money
 out now, Beaufort.

681
00:34:02,500 --> 00:34:04,940
He seemed especially
 vindictive today.

682
00:34:11,560 --> 00:34:15,270
OK, we're ready to begin
 a cabin leak at six minutes

683
00:34:15,270 --> 00:34:17,860
before main engine cutoff.

684
00:34:17,860 --> 00:34:18,930
How many of these do you want?

685
00:34:18,930 --> 00:34:19,680
You've had two.

686
00:34:19,680 --> 00:34:21,350
Come on, I didn't
 have breakfast.

687
00:34:21,350 --> 00:34:25,120
At two minutes before cut
 off, fail the computers.

688
00:34:25,120 --> 00:34:26,520
Computer switches?

689
00:34:26,520 --> 00:34:28,230
Got them.

690
00:34:28,230 --> 00:34:29,940
Let him be vindictive.

691
00:34:29,940 --> 00:34:32,970
They won't get one by us.

692
00:34:32,970 --> 00:34:34,530
You want any?

693
00:34:34,530 --> 00:34:35,230
Yes.

694
00:34:39,090 --> 00:34:40,780
You got my little green pen?

695
00:34:40,780 --> 00:34:41,480
No.

696
00:34:41,480 --> 00:34:42,510
We've got pens right there.

697
00:34:42,510 --> 00:34:44,110
I know, but I like the
 one with the little--

698
00:34:44,110 --> 00:34:45,960
Brake.

699
00:34:45,960 --> 00:34:48,290
All right, we're reset.

700
00:34:48,290 --> 00:34:49,910
Let's tighten up.

701
00:34:49,910 --> 00:34:51,760
OK, resetting.

702
00:34:51,760 --> 00:34:54,370
I want that cabin leak
 right after liftoff.

703
00:34:54,370 --> 00:34:56,570
OK, it says a 6 inch
 hole in the cabin.

704
00:34:56,570 --> 00:34:58,200
That's be big enough
 to pull people through.

705
00:34:58,200 --> 00:34:59,410
Must mean 6/10 of an inch.

706
00:34:59,410 --> 00:35:00,110
Yeah, 6/10.

707
00:35:00,110 --> 00:35:02,220
It couldn't be 6 inches.

708
00:35:02,220 --> 00:35:03,170
Ready in the simulator.

709
00:35:03,170 --> 00:35:03,870
Ready.

710
00:35:03,870 --> 00:35:04,570
Ready.

711
00:35:04,570 --> 00:35:06,480
It's getting boring up here.

712
00:35:06,480 --> 00:35:09,150
Ah so, please forgive.

713
00:35:09,150 --> 00:35:11,910
All right, start them.

714
00:35:11,910 --> 00:35:15,030
T minus 8 seconds.

715
00:35:15,030 --> 00:35:17,880
OK, we have three
 engines burning at 100%.

716
00:35:17,880 --> 00:35:19,970
3, 2, 1.

717
00:35:28,960 --> 00:35:30,860
Here's the roll program.

718
00:35:30,860 --> 00:35:32,180
Roger will, Challenger.

719
00:35:32,180 --> 00:35:32,880
LBLH.

720
00:35:37,970 --> 00:35:38,700
Throttle down.

721
00:35:46,380 --> 00:35:48,140
And throttle up.

722
00:35:48,140 --> 00:35:49,620
Going throttle up, Challenger?

723
00:35:49,620 --> 00:35:51,660
Roger, going throttle up.

724
00:35:51,660 --> 00:35:53,850
Boosters separated.

725
00:35:53,850 --> 00:35:55,200
Negative return.

726
00:35:55,200 --> 00:35:55,900
Roger.

727
00:35:59,750 --> 00:36:01,510
Challenger press to orbit.

728
00:36:01,510 --> 00:36:05,240
Roger, press to orbit.

729
00:36:05,240 --> 00:36:06,710
Cabin leak, Scobe.

730
00:36:06,710 --> 00:36:08,910
Relief valves.

731
00:36:08,910 --> 00:36:09,750
Already checked.

732
00:36:09,750 --> 00:36:11,760
What's cabin pressure?

733
00:36:11,760 --> 00:36:15,130
Down to 14.2 PSI.

734
00:36:15,130 --> 00:36:17,740
There's nothing to do except
 cycle the relief valves.

735
00:36:17,740 --> 00:36:20,310
That's right.

736
00:36:20,310 --> 00:36:22,200
Right and they're closed.

737
00:36:22,200 --> 00:36:23,810
For record, did you
 make it, not a gusher.

738
00:36:23,810 --> 00:36:24,510
No, it's right.

739
00:36:24,510 --> 00:36:26,350
It's real.

740
00:36:26,350 --> 00:36:28,250
Standby for a curve ball
 in a couple of minutes.

741
00:36:28,250 --> 00:36:28,950
I'm ready.

742
00:36:28,950 --> 00:36:31,160
I've got a good one for them.

743
00:36:31,160 --> 00:36:32,150
That didn't stop the leak.

744
00:36:32,150 --> 00:36:35,180
Better get ready to abort.

745
00:36:35,180 --> 00:36:37,670
We've got the velocity
 for Dakar or Conchesa.

746
00:36:37,670 --> 00:36:39,170
There's a Club Med at Dakar.

747
00:36:39,170 --> 00:36:40,850
Let's go there.

748
00:36:40,850 --> 00:36:42,830
I'm slowing the leak,
 give them a better chance.

749
00:36:42,830 --> 00:36:44,330
Soon as they pick
 their abort site,

750
00:36:44,330 --> 00:36:46,620
we'll toss in another
 couple of malfs.

751
00:36:46,620 --> 00:36:47,950
Hold on, what's
 their cabin pressure?

752
00:36:47,950 --> 00:36:48,650
It's dropping.

753
00:36:48,650 --> 00:36:50,040
It's close to 10.

754
00:36:50,040 --> 00:36:51,430
I failed a caution
 warning light.

755
00:36:51,430 --> 00:36:53,730
They probably won't
 notice it yet.

756
00:36:53,730 --> 00:36:57,200
Abort to Dakar now.

757
00:36:57,200 --> 00:36:59,850
Abort to Dakar.

758
00:36:59,850 --> 00:37:01,430
UMS are dumping.

759
00:37:01,430 --> 00:37:03,900
And valves are configured.

760
00:37:03,900 --> 00:37:05,590
What's cabin pressure?

761
00:37:05,590 --> 00:37:06,650
A little under 10 PSI.

762
00:37:06,650 --> 00:37:09,830
Seems to be slowing slightly.

763
00:37:09,830 --> 00:37:11,720
This is where they
 get paid the big bucks.

764
00:37:11,720 --> 00:37:12,620
Let's beat them up.

765
00:37:12,620 --> 00:37:14,460
I'll kill one of
 the main engines.

766
00:37:14,460 --> 00:37:15,830
Still gonna make Dakar?

767
00:37:15,830 --> 00:37:17,080
Trust me.

768
00:37:17,080 --> 00:37:18,080
Go ahead.

769
00:37:22,070 --> 00:37:23,200
Left main engine gone.

770
00:37:23,200 --> 00:37:24,580
Guide and seize it.

771
00:37:24,580 --> 00:37:27,290
The other two engines
 half throttled up.

772
00:37:27,290 --> 00:37:30,030
Looks like we have enough
 energy to still make Dakar.

773
00:37:30,030 --> 00:37:33,120
They'll make Dakar but
 they'll have to do an OHMS burn.

774
00:37:33,120 --> 00:37:35,060
We have main engine cutoff.

775
00:37:35,060 --> 00:37:37,310
What's our final velocity?

776
00:37:37,310 --> 00:37:39,930
I don't know if we're going
 to have to do an OHMS burn.

777
00:37:39,930 --> 00:37:43,400
What a guide, Mike.

778
00:37:43,400 --> 00:37:44,870
External tank separated.

779
00:37:44,870 --> 00:37:46,760
We'll turn off the
 OHMS engines mainly

780
00:37:46,760 --> 00:37:48,290
once they burn long enough.

781
00:37:48,290 --> 00:37:50,450
I don't know if we
 have to do that, Scobe.

782
00:37:50,450 --> 00:37:52,070
They don't have to do that.

783
00:37:52,070 --> 00:37:53,510
When the engine shuts
 off automatically,

784
00:37:53,510 --> 00:37:55,920
they'll see that they
 don't have to do that.

785
00:37:55,920 --> 00:37:57,860
Yep, the computer
 automatically

