1044
00:51:08,710 --> 00:51:10,570
I'll tell you one
 thing, I want to be

1045
00:51:10,570 --> 00:51:13,950
photographed from the waist
 up when I'm doing my lessons.

1046
00:51:13,950 --> 00:51:15,790
Those are lovely.

1047
00:51:15,790 --> 00:51:17,050
Also, you know,
 you'll be an inch

1048
00:51:17,050 --> 00:51:18,370
and a half taller in space.

1049
00:51:18,370 --> 00:51:19,150
Oh, that's right.

1050
00:51:19,150 --> 00:51:21,940
That would help.

1051
00:51:21,940 --> 00:51:23,990
These black boots are
 what you wear for launch.

1052
00:51:23,990 --> 00:51:25,190
Very smart.

1053
00:51:25,190 --> 00:51:27,940
And these leather
 soled woolen moccasins

1054
00:51:27,940 --> 00:51:30,350
are for comfort in orbit.

1055
00:51:30,350 --> 00:51:31,130
These are terrific.

1056
00:51:34,840 --> 00:51:38,400
Oh, look at that.

1057
00:51:38,400 --> 00:51:40,670
My kids don't really believe
 I'm going up into space.

1058
00:51:40,670 --> 00:51:42,570
I'd like to walk into the room
 in the middle of the night

1059
00:51:42,570 --> 00:51:45,360
with one of those on.

1060
00:51:45,360 --> 00:51:49,700
Now here's something
 for your diet, space food.

1061
00:51:49,700 --> 00:51:52,010
You'll select the
 meals you eat on orbit.

1062
00:51:52,010 --> 00:51:53,780
Your meals will be color coded.

1063
00:51:53,780 --> 00:51:56,690
We've got 140 food
 and beverage items.

1064
00:51:56,690 --> 00:51:58,090
Who wants to go first?

1065
00:51:58,090 --> 00:51:58,790
I'll start.

1066
00:52:03,840 --> 00:52:05,300
It's got cafeteria food beat.

1067
00:52:05,300 --> 00:52:06,370
Uh-huh.

1068
00:52:06,370 --> 00:52:08,020
They do chicken right.

1069
00:52:08,020 --> 00:52:09,850
When you're hungry, you
 just float over, pick out

1070
00:52:09,850 --> 00:52:13,290
your color, and start batting.

1071
00:52:13,290 --> 00:52:15,190
Float over.

1072
00:52:15,190 --> 00:52:18,110
Every once in a while, I
 sort of stand outside myself

1073
00:52:18,110 --> 00:52:20,720
and I realize what I'm doing.

1074
00:52:20,720 --> 00:52:22,430
Oh, try the broccoli.

1075
00:52:22,430 --> 00:52:24,790
It's delicious.

1076
00:52:24,790 --> 00:52:26,260
Sprouts.

1077
00:52:26,260 --> 00:52:27,030
Want more?

1078
00:52:27,030 --> 00:52:27,730
No, you.

1079
00:52:27,730 --> 00:52:28,600
You haven't eaten any.

1080
00:52:28,600 --> 00:52:29,530
I will.

1081
00:52:29,530 --> 00:52:30,750
Did Dad call?

1082
00:52:30,750 --> 00:52:31,580
No.

1083
00:52:31,580 --> 00:52:32,980
Did he say you would
 be here for dinner?

1084
00:52:32,980 --> 00:52:34,880
Nope.

1085
00:52:34,880 --> 00:52:36,370
Maybe it's one of
 those times when he says

1086
00:52:36,370 --> 00:52:37,870
it's impossible to get here?

1087
00:52:37,870 --> 00:52:41,280
Yeah, maybe rainfalls
 up instead of down too.

1088
00:52:41,280 --> 00:52:43,980
Eat your fish.

1089
00:52:43,980 --> 00:52:44,680
Try them.

1090
00:52:44,680 --> 00:52:47,140
I used to run around the islands
 picking these when I was a kid.

1091
00:52:47,140 --> 00:52:48,010
They're good, El.

1092
00:52:48,010 --> 00:52:48,790
What are they called?

1093
00:52:48,790 --> 00:52:49,610
Macadamia nuts.

1094
00:52:49,610 --> 00:52:51,010
Eat them with your
 beer, guaranteed you'll

1095
00:52:51,010 --> 00:52:52,540
gain 30 pounds in one night.

1096
00:52:52,540 --> 00:52:53,900
It's my turn.

1097
00:52:53,900 --> 00:52:54,640
Hey, wait a minute.

1098
00:52:54,640 --> 00:52:55,950
I'm next on that pool game.

1099
00:52:55,950 --> 00:52:57,200
Let me go next, El.

1100
00:52:57,200 --> 00:52:59,290
I need revenge on Brandenstein.

1101
00:52:59,290 --> 00:53:01,190
All right, all right,
 but I'm next, OK?

1102
00:53:01,190 --> 00:53:03,860
I got dinner waiting at home.

1103
00:53:03,860 --> 00:53:05,200
You should have
 brought the plans,

1104
00:53:05,200 --> 00:53:07,360
I could point right to where
 you should make revisions.

1105
00:53:07,360 --> 00:53:08,720
We took a good long look.

1106
00:53:08,720 --> 00:53:11,240
Those plans don't have
 to be revised, JR.

1107
00:53:11,240 --> 00:53:13,510
Mark, there are
 three specific errors.

1108
00:53:13,510 --> 00:53:14,560
They don't exist.

1109
00:53:14,560 --> 00:53:15,960
We didn't find them.

1110
00:53:15,960 --> 00:53:16,960
They do exist.

1111
00:53:16,960 --> 00:53:19,140
The remote arm cannot
 grab that satellite

1112
00:53:19,140 --> 00:53:21,070
the way it's positioned
 in the payload bay.

1113
00:53:21,070 --> 00:53:22,370
I'm not guessing at this.

1114
00:53:22,370 --> 00:53:25,620
JR, there are four
 of us and one of you.

1115
00:53:25,620 --> 00:53:29,010
Now, four guys can't be
 wrong, or am I treading

1116
00:53:29,010 --> 00:53:30,550
on your feminist views?

1117
00:53:30,550 --> 00:53:31,720
You're doing worse.

1118
00:53:31,720 --> 00:53:33,310
You're arguing with
 someone who knows

1119
00:53:33,310 --> 00:53:36,400
everything that's possible to
 know about that remote arm.

1120
00:53:36,400 --> 00:53:37,990
Think about this, Mark.

1121
00:53:37,990 --> 00:53:41,080
I'm the one who launches a
 $50 million piece of equipment

1122
00:53:41,080 --> 00:53:44,520
off the shuttle in front of
 the onboard television cameras,

1123
00:53:44,520 --> 00:53:46,220
and I don't get it wrong.

1124
00:53:46,220 --> 00:53:47,060
So check it out, OK?

1125
00:53:50,110 --> 00:53:52,750
And you're treading
 on my feminist views.

1126
00:53:52,750 --> 00:53:54,240
I don't know what to tell you.

1127
00:53:54,240 --> 00:53:55,840
Want to make a bet you're wrong?

1128
00:53:55,840 --> 00:53:57,480
What kind of bet?

1129
00:53:57,480 --> 00:54:00,400
Well, if I'm right,
 you go to dinner with me.

1130
00:54:00,400 --> 00:54:01,510
And if I'm right?

1131
00:54:01,510 --> 00:54:03,190
Then that would be bad.

1132
00:54:03,190 --> 00:54:04,450
I'd have to go to
 dinner with you.

1133
00:54:28,210 --> 00:54:31,700
[SINGING]

1134
00:54:33,190 --> 00:54:34,340
Hey.

1135
00:54:34,340 --> 00:54:35,880
Where are the kids?

1136
00:54:35,880 --> 00:54:38,390
They're in bed, El.

1137
00:54:38,390 --> 00:54:40,940
OK, I can work with that.

1138
00:54:40,940 --> 00:54:41,870
Is dinner ready?

1139
00:54:47,140 --> 00:54:48,170
Why are you closing the window?

1140
00:54:48,170 --> 00:54:48,870
It's hot.

1141
00:54:48,870 --> 00:54:51,840
I'm closing the windows
 because I'm going to shout.

1142
00:54:51,840 --> 00:54:54,170
Don't shout.

1143
00:54:58,610 --> 00:55:00,860
I'm going to eat
 for three weeks

1144
00:55:00,860 --> 00:55:03,500
straight and make my
 rear end so big you

1145
00:55:03,500 --> 00:55:07,880
won't be able to get around
 it to get in to this house.

1146
00:55:07,880 --> 00:55:09,530
What do you mean
 coming home at 2:30

1147
00:55:09,530 --> 00:55:11,390
in the morning with
 that breath belching

1148
00:55:11,390 --> 00:55:14,360
stupid questions like where are
 the kids and where's my dinner?

1149
00:55:14,360 --> 00:55:15,320
I've been waiting.

1150
00:55:15,320 --> 00:55:16,310
Your kids have been waiting.

1151
00:55:16,310 --> 00:55:17,690
I fixed your dinner
 and you didn't

1152
00:55:17,690 --> 00:55:18,730
even have the decency to call.

1153
00:55:18,730 --> 00:55:19,430
What?

1154
00:55:19,430 --> 00:55:21,200
I had a couple of
 beers at the Outpost.

1155
00:55:21,200 --> 00:55:24,670
You had 40 beers
 at the Outpost.

1156
00:55:24,670 --> 00:55:25,430
Where's dinner?

1157
00:55:25,430 --> 00:55:26,690
You said you made dinner.

1158
00:55:26,690 --> 00:55:27,950
It's at the bottom
 of the garbage.

1159
00:55:27,950 --> 00:55:29,190
You go paw through it.

1160
00:55:29,190 --> 00:55:30,900
Lorna, why are we shouting?

1161
00:55:30,900 --> 00:55:32,030
You're not shouting.

1162
00:55:32,030 --> 00:55:34,150
I'm shouting.

1163
00:55:34,150 --> 00:55:36,230
Because you're never home.

1164
00:55:36,230 --> 00:55:38,050
It's because this
 isn't the life I wanted

1165
00:55:38,050 --> 00:55:40,540
and it is because of that
 stack of technical documents

1166
00:55:40,540 --> 00:55:42,190
always piled up on that table.

1167
00:55:42,190 --> 00:55:43,930
I've grown to hate it.

1168
00:55:43,930 --> 00:55:45,760
I want to burn it.

1169
00:55:45,760 --> 00:55:47,290
Why can't we have
 a home without it?

1170
00:55:47,290 --> 00:55:50,170
A little shack that has
 nothing to do with NASA?

1171
00:55:50,170 --> 00:55:53,890
We can as soon as the flight
 is over, we'll take a vacation.

1172
00:55:53,890 --> 00:55:55,210
Vacation?

1173
00:55:55,210 --> 00:55:57,820
That word doesn't exist
 in your vocabulary.

1174
00:56:01,380 --> 00:56:02,940
You can't do this, El.

1175
00:56:05,630 --> 00:56:09,090
You can't work 100 hour weeks.

1176
00:56:09,090 --> 00:56:11,190
And you're away on these
 Defense Department assignments

1177
00:56:11,190 --> 00:56:14,360
where we don't know where
 you are, you call us,

1178
00:56:14,360 --> 00:56:18,380
but we don't know where you
 are or when you're coming home.

1179
00:56:18,380 --> 00:56:20,090
You have 30 days
 vacation a year.

1180
00:56:20,090 --> 00:56:21,770
You haven't taken one
 in the past seven.

1181
00:56:25,000 --> 00:56:27,950
NASA is not just my job.

1182
00:56:27,950 --> 00:56:28,650
It's my life.

1183
00:56:31,480 --> 00:56:34,570
I made a commitment years ago.

1184
00:56:34,570 --> 00:56:38,010
You made it with me.

1185
00:56:38,010 --> 00:56:41,160
Whatever I do, I have to do it
 well or I don't do it at all.

1186
00:56:50,020 --> 00:56:52,950
I'll try to do better, Lorna.

1187
00:56:52,950 --> 00:56:55,130
No, don't do better.

1188
00:56:55,130 --> 00:56:57,950
Do worse.

1189
00:56:57,950 --> 00:56:58,700
Do less.

1190
00:56:58,700 --> 00:57:02,440
Just-- just stop, El.

1191
00:57:02,440 --> 00:57:03,490
Be with us.

1192
00:57:06,010 --> 00:57:08,250
The girls and I are a
 part of your life too.

1193
00:57:12,410 --> 00:57:13,390
Just come home.

1194
00:57:16,190 --> 00:57:16,990
We miss you.

1195
00:57:22,470 --> 00:57:25,250
And we take that vacation.

1196
00:57:25,250 --> 00:57:25,950
I promise.

1197
00:57:32,490 --> 00:57:34,900
This is not some grievance
 committee from the unions, Joe.

1198
00:57:34,900 --> 00:57:37,240
These guys are members
 of the task force.

1199
00:57:37,240 --> 00:57:39,360
They have a serious problem.

1200
00:57:39,360 --> 00:57:42,360
The problem is the task
 force isn't getting anywhere.

1201
00:57:42,360 --> 00:57:43,850
It doesn't have a priority.

1202
00:57:43,850 --> 00:57:47,030
Roger, all three of
 you, Morton-Thiokol

1203
00:57:47,030 --> 00:57:48,620
commissioned this task force.

1204
00:57:48,620 --> 00:57:51,550
We saw a need for
 it and created it.

1205
00:57:51,550 --> 00:57:53,820
It has a priority here.

1206
00:57:53,820 --> 00:57:57,320
The word priority doesn't mean
 anything important at Thiokol.

1207
00:57:57,320 --> 00:58:01,370
All priorities have
 the same priority.

1208
00:58:01,370 --> 00:58:04,220
Roger, you work
 on one component

1209
00:58:04,220 --> 00:58:05,870
of a single system
 of which there

1210
00:58:05,870 --> 00:58:07,010
are hundreds in the shuttle.

1211
00:58:07,010 --> 00:58:09,500
You know your component well.

1212
00:58:09,500 --> 00:58:12,070
What you don't know is how
 a corporation is managed.

1213
00:58:15,010 --> 00:58:17,740
That's something that
 I'm paid to know, right?

1214
00:58:17,740 --> 00:58:20,250
And when I say that something
 has a priority, by God,

1215
00:58:20,250 --> 00:58:23,750
it has a priority.

1216
00:58:23,750 --> 00:58:26,770
This is a requisition
 for a function generator.

1217
00:58:26,770 --> 00:58:29,890
We placed the order
 priority on September 24th.

1218
00:58:29,890 --> 00:58:32,380
It's 10 days later, there's
 still no sign of it.

1219
00:58:32,380 --> 00:58:34,290
This is a typical experience.

1220
00:58:34,290 --> 00:58:36,580
Joe, this is a cry for help.

1221
00:58:36,580 --> 00:58:38,410
We run into delays
 everywhere and every time

1222
00:58:38,410 --> 00:58:40,660
we try to do something.

1223
00:58:40,660 --> 00:58:41,490
This is a red flag.

1224
00:58:44,340 --> 00:58:45,640
All right.

1225
00:58:45,640 --> 00:58:48,500
Then you better tell me
 everything you're thinking.

1226
00:58:48,500 --> 00:58:50,210
I'll tell you
 what I'm thinking.

1227
00:58:50,210 --> 00:58:51,750
I'm thinking maybe
 Morton-Thiokol

1228
00:58:51,750 --> 00:58:53,610
is trying to slow us down.

1229
00:58:53,610 --> 00:58:55,490
Maybe they're afraid our
 task force will find out

1230
00:58:55,490 --> 00:58:57,110
that the solid
 rocket boosters never

1231
00:58:57,110 --> 00:58:59,980
should have been made with
 O-rings in the first place.

1232
00:58:59,980 --> 00:59:02,150
That the O-rings can never
 be made strong enough

1233
00:59:02,150 --> 00:59:04,770
to contain the hot gases.

1234
00:59:04,770 --> 00:59:07,100
Maybe that's why we run
 into so many obstacles.

1235
00:59:07,100 --> 00:59:09,100
How dare you make an
 accusation like that?

1236
00:59:09,100 --> 00:59:10,540
Do you know what you're saying?

1237
00:59:10,540 --> 00:59:13,280
You're darn right I
 know what I'm saying.

1238
00:59:13,280 --> 00:59:14,500
I'm saying what's
 the explanation

1239
00:59:14,500 --> 00:59:18,120
of why things go so slow?

1240
00:59:18,120 --> 00:59:21,100
Even NASA sees
 were being blocked.

1241
00:59:21,100 --> 00:59:23,030
They're sending an engineer
 next week to monitor

1242
00:59:23,030 --> 00:59:24,770
the progress of our task force.

1243
00:59:24,770 --> 00:59:25,590
Did you know about that?

1244
00:59:25,590 --> 00:59:26,420
Of course, I know that.

1245
00:59:26,420 --> 00:59:28,490
We got a problem, Joe.

1246
00:59:28,490 --> 00:59:30,090
We need a way to
 get our work done.

1247
00:59:30,090 --> 00:59:31,400
It's as simple as that.

1248
00:59:31,400 --> 00:59:32,900
There's a problem,
 all right, and I can see

1249
00:59:32,900 --> 00:59:35,060
it right here in front of me.

1250
00:59:35,060 --> 00:59:37,340
You people want to go around
 the established system.

1251
00:59:37,340 --> 00:59:39,320
That's possible in
 some cases, but nobody

1252
00:59:39,320 --> 00:59:41,030
can take shortcuts
 that risk damaging

1253
00:59:41,030 --> 00:59:42,800
the flight hardware we produce.

1254
00:59:42,800 --> 00:59:45,740
Our first job is to provide the
 boosters that fly that shuttle.

1255
00:59:45,740 --> 00:59:47,240
That's the point.

1256
00:59:47,240 --> 00:59:49,730
We're supposed to find out if
 it's safe to fly the shuttle,

1257
00:59:49,730 --> 00:59:51,270
and we can't get our work done.

1258
00:59:51,270 --> 00:59:53,930
Oh, you can get
 your work done.

1259
00:59:53,930 --> 00:59:56,270
When you come across a
 problem, you handle it.

1260
00:59:56,270 --> 00:59:57,620
You don't come crying in here.

1261
00:59:57,620 --> 00:59:59,730
You don't look for somebody
 else to get it solved.

1262
00:59:59,730 --> 01:00:00,430
You solve it.

1263
01:00:06,710 --> 01:00:07,880
You've been here a long time.

1264
01:00:07,880 --> 01:00:09,340
You know what I'm talking about.

1265
01:00:13,710 --> 01:00:16,590
Now we want a solution to the
 O-ring problem from this task

1266
01:00:16,590 --> 01:00:18,310
force and we're going
 to have a solution,

1267
01:00:18,310 --> 01:00:20,460
and it's going to be one that
 does not endanger production

1268
01:00:20,460 --> 01:00:22,690
quality or production schedule.

1269
01:00:22,690 --> 01:00:24,120
That's what I've
 got to tell you.

1270
01:00:24,120 --> 01:00:25,070
That's all.

1271
01:00:30,810 --> 01:00:34,180
I'm telling you, Joe,
 Morton-Thiokol should not ship

1272
01:00:34,180 --> 01:00:36,520
any more solid rocket
 boosters, not until

1273
01:00:36,520 --> 01:00:37,810
this O-ring problem is fixed.

1274
01:01:13,030 --> 01:01:15,280
Excuse me, aren't
 you what's her name?

1275
01:01:15,280 --> 01:01:16,080
Yes.

1276
01:01:16,080 --> 01:01:16,840
Christa McAuliffe.

1277
01:01:16,840 --> 01:01:19,860
Well, congratulations to
 you going up into space.

1278
01:01:19,860 --> 01:01:20,560
Thank you.

1279
01:01:20,560 --> 01:01:21,260
I can hardly wait.

1280
01:01:21,260 --> 01:01:22,050
We won't keep you.

1281
01:01:22,050 --> 01:01:23,890
We know you want to
 get on with your trip,

1282
01:01:23,890 --> 01:01:25,950
but it's just so exciting
 to talk to you for a minute.

1283
01:01:25,950 --> 01:01:26,650
Thank you.

1284
01:01:26,650 --> 01:01:28,510
You have a wonderful
 time down here.

1285
01:01:28,510 --> 01:01:30,360
You have a wonderful
 time up there.

1286
01:01:30,360 --> 01:01:31,090
Thank you.

1287
01:01:31,090 --> 01:01:33,180
All of America
 is proud of you.

1288
01:01:33,180 --> 01:01:33,880
So proud.

1289
01:01:39,680 --> 01:01:40,680
Howdy.

1290
01:01:40,680 --> 01:01:41,380
Hi.

1291
01:01:41,380 --> 01:01:42,140
Bob Mayfield.

1292
01:01:42,140 --> 01:01:43,740
Hi, Bob.

1293
01:01:43,740 --> 01:01:45,730
I've been looking
 forward to our meeting.

1294
01:01:45,730 --> 01:01:49,280
I'll be working with
 you on the lesson plans.

1295
01:01:49,280 --> 01:01:51,170
Sorry for the tardiness.

1296
01:01:51,170 --> 01:01:52,670
I feel I need to
 respond to people,

1297
01:01:52,670 --> 01:01:54,460
but it can sure throw
 your schedule off.

1298
01:01:54,460 --> 01:01:57,620
Add three hours off
 by about 20 minutes.

1299
01:01:57,620 --> 01:01:58,430
Really?

1300
01:01:58,430 --> 01:02:00,420
Well that and whatever
 else is going on.

1301
01:02:00,420 --> 01:02:03,030
Time sure can slip by.

1302
01:02:03,030 --> 01:02:05,660
Anyway, shall we talk
 about the lesson plans?

1303
01:02:05,660 --> 01:02:08,180
Yes, naturally I
 have some questions.

1304
01:02:08,180 --> 01:02:10,430
Mainly, I wish I'd been
 consulted before the lesson

1305
01:02:10,430 --> 01:02:12,110
plan got into a final form.

1306
01:02:12,110 --> 01:02:14,120
Well, they had to be
 finalized before the teacher

1307
01:02:14,120 --> 01:02:17,480
was selected because there's
 so much hardware to create.

1308
01:02:17,480 --> 01:02:18,760
Time is another problem.

1309
01:02:18,760 --> 01:02:21,050
Lesson plans have
 to get scripted.

1310
01:02:21,050 --> 01:02:21,750
Scripted?

1311
01:02:21,750 --> 01:02:22,450
Right.

1312
01:02:22,450 --> 01:02:23,240
Why?

1313
01:02:23,240 --> 01:02:24,470
Scheduling is one
 of most important

1314
01:02:24,470 --> 01:02:25,610
elements in a shuttle flight.

1315
01:02:25,610 --> 01:02:29,220
Everything's got to be
 timed and slotted exactly.

1316
01:02:29,220 --> 01:02:31,490
All right, when I know
 how much time I've got,

1317
01:02:31,490 --> 01:02:34,700
I'll fit my lesson plan to that.

1318
01:02:34,700 --> 01:02:36,330
Well, I don't
 think that'll work.

1319
01:02:36,330 --> 01:02:38,320
NASA wants every
 word written down.

1320
01:02:38,320 --> 01:02:39,590
Well, NASA really
 should have talked

1321
01:02:39,590 --> 01:02:40,940
to a teacher about all this.

1322
01:02:40,940 --> 01:02:41,740
They did.

1323
01:02:41,740 --> 01:02:42,440
I'm a teacher.

1324
01:02:45,190 --> 01:02:48,080
Well, then, Bob, you
 know what I'm saying?

1325
01:02:48,080 --> 01:02:49,280
This isn't a stage play.

1326
01:02:49,280 --> 01:02:50,780
Teachers don't need speeches.

1327
01:02:50,780 --> 01:02:53,110
All they need is their lesson
 plan and their students.

1328
01:02:53,110 --> 01:02:55,710
It's worked for ages on earth,
 why shouldn't it work in space?

1329
01:02:55,710 --> 01:02:58,180
Well, others will
 make that decision.

1330
01:02:58,180 --> 01:03:00,270
Anything else?

1331
01:03:00,270 --> 01:03:04,370
I don't see why there's
 so much emphasis on science.

1332
01:03:04,370 --> 01:03:06,140
Shuttle's basically
 a scientific vehicle

1333
01:03:06,140 --> 01:03:09,440
that gives us a platform where
 space science can be performed

1334
01:03:09,440 --> 01:03:11,570
in front of millions of people.

1335
01:03:11,570 --> 01:03:13,760
Yes, but a lot of
 people besides scientists

1336
01:03:13,760 --> 01:03:16,160
will be involved in
 space in the future.

1337
01:03:16,160 --> 01:03:18,620
There will be space
 schools, space post

1338
01:03:18,620 --> 01:03:20,420
offices, space
 construction, space

1339
01:03:20,420 --> 01:03:22,940
restaurants, space everything.

1340
01:03:22,940 --> 01:03:24,950
I'd like my students
 to see themselves

1341
01:03:24,950 --> 01:03:26,600
as a part of that big picture.

1342
01:03:26,600 --> 01:03:29,960
That'd probably be a good
 idea in about 20 years.

1343
01:03:29,960 --> 01:03:32,870
I mean, right now, we don't
 have any space post offices

1344
01:03:32,870 --> 01:03:34,910
or space restaurants, so
 experiments about them

1345
01:03:34,910 --> 01:03:36,710
won't be much help.

1346
01:03:36,710 --> 01:03:38,890
It feels to me that the
 first lesson from space

1347
01:03:38,890 --> 01:03:40,460
ought to be something
 everybody can understand.

1348
01:03:40,460 --> 01:03:42,950
Of course, but I think
 we should be sending

1349
01:03:42,950 --> 01:03:45,050
something more to our
 classrooms than just

1350
01:03:45,050 --> 01:03:48,940
scientific experiments.

1351
01:03:48,940 --> 01:03:50,920
I don't get what
 you're saying.

1352
01:03:50,920 --> 01:03:52,390
Is it that you don't
 know much about science

1353
01:03:52,390 --> 01:03:54,060
or you want to put your
 experience on this mission

1354
01:03:54,060 --> 01:03:56,040
into a social studies course?

1355
01:03:56,040 --> 01:03:58,070
What I'm saying is
 that NASA selected

1356
01:03:58,070 --> 01:03:59,640
me because I'm a good teacher.

1357
01:03:59,640 --> 01:04:00,950
I think they're
 right, and I don't

1358
01:04:00,950 --> 01:04:05,100
think I need additional
 instruction in how to do that.

1359
01:04:05,100 --> 01:04:08,220
Being the first teacher in
 space is a tremendous thrill,

1360
01:04:08,220 --> 01:04:10,070
but it's not a
 personal trophy for me.

1361
01:04:10,070 --> 01:04:14,220
Christa McAuliffe, one
 teacher, isn't the point.

1362
01:04:14,220 --> 01:04:15,830
It's teaching.

1363
01:04:15,830 --> 01:04:18,800
Teachers being acknowledged
 for the shaping hand

1364
01:04:18,800 --> 01:04:22,970
they lay on the young
 lives of our country.

1365
01:04:22,970 --> 01:04:24,020
Commander Scobee?

1366
01:04:24,020 --> 01:04:25,370
Right.

1367
01:04:25,370 --> 01:04:26,960
My name is Greg Jarvis.

1368
01:04:26,960 --> 01:04:27,660
All right.

1369
01:04:27,660 --> 01:04:28,920
How's it going, Greg Jarvis?

1370
01:04:28,920 --> 01:04:30,290
Listen, I don't want
 to bother you now.

1371
01:04:30,290 --> 01:04:33,660
I know you're busy
 preparing for the mission.

1372
01:04:33,660 --> 01:04:35,630
I might be going with you.

1373
01:04:35,630 --> 01:04:36,830
Well, is that so?

1374
01:04:36,830 --> 01:04:38,730
Yeah, it's just
 a rumor still, but

1375
01:04:38,730 --> 01:04:40,100
in case I wind up
 on your shuttle,

1376
01:04:40,100 --> 01:04:41,390
I wanted to introduce myself.

1377
01:04:41,390 --> 01:04:42,090
I'm--

1378
01:04:42,090 --> 01:04:43,150
You're Greg Jarvis.

1379
01:04:43,150 --> 01:04:43,850
Yeah.

1380
01:04:43,850 --> 01:04:44,550
No.

1381
01:04:44,550 --> 01:04:46,230
Well.

1382
01:04:46,230 --> 01:04:48,200
But what I was going
 to say was, I'm

1383
01:04:48,200 --> 01:04:51,100
really excited because I was
 assigned to two other missions

1384
01:04:51,100 --> 01:04:53,450
and I was bumped both
 times, first by Senator Garn

1385
01:04:53,450 --> 01:04:54,650
and then by Congressman Nelson.

1386
01:04:54,650 --> 01:04:56,450
Well, what are you
 going to be doing?

1387
01:04:56,450 --> 01:04:58,220
Experiments on
 how fluids behave

1388
01:04:58,220 --> 01:05:00,020
in an orbiting space vehicle.

1389
01:05:00,020 --> 01:05:01,320
I'm an engineer at Hughes.

1390
01:05:01,320 --> 01:05:03,860
I won a contest to
 go on the shuttle.

1391
01:05:03,860 --> 01:05:04,820
Well, congratulations.

1392
01:05:04,820 --> 01:05:06,890
Listen, I'm glad
 to meet you Greg,

1393
01:05:06,890 --> 01:05:10,210
but I'm not glad to hear about
 more experiments coming aboard.

1394
01:05:10,210 --> 01:05:12,870
You think it'll be a problem?

1395
01:05:12,870 --> 01:05:14,150
It's hard for me
 to explain to you

1396
01:05:14,150 --> 01:05:16,220
just how big a problem it is.

1397
01:05:16,220 --> 01:05:19,110
You see, by adding a
 passenger and his experiments

1398
01:05:19,110 --> 01:05:21,580
that means total
 redistribution of crew space.

1399
01:05:21,580 --> 01:05:25,780
It means revision of
 this activity plan here.

1400
01:05:25,780 --> 01:05:27,830
You've already got all
 of this paraphernalia

1401
01:05:27,830 --> 01:05:31,060
for Christa McAuliffe
 experiments.

1402
01:05:31,060 --> 01:05:32,690
For example, now she's
 going to be doing a lesson

1403
01:05:32,690 --> 01:05:33,650
in space about magnetism.

1404
01:05:33,650 --> 01:05:36,090
Now, they wanted to bring
 iron filings aboard.

1405
01:05:36,090 --> 01:05:37,340
Now, can you picture this?

1406
01:05:37,340 --> 01:05:38,710
If those iron filings
 had ever gotten out

1407
01:05:38,710 --> 01:05:40,110
of the container, first
 of all, they would

1408
01:05:40,110 --> 01:05:41,240
have been inhaled by the crew.

1409
01:05:41,240 --> 01:05:42,970
They would've gotten into
 the electronics equipment.

1410
01:05:42,970 --> 01:05:45,380
Commander, if I'm lucky
 enough to go on this mission,

1411
01:05:45,380 --> 01:05:47,050
I'll do everything I
 can to make it simple.

1412
01:05:47,050 --> 01:05:47,750
I'll make it easy.

1413
01:05:51,040 --> 01:05:51,740
Good luck.

1414
01:06:10,060 --> 01:06:11,210
Watch your head.

1415
01:06:11,210 --> 01:06:11,930
Good boy.

1416
01:06:15,800 --> 01:06:21,290
All right, now, these are the
 lockers where all the food

1417
01:06:21,290 --> 01:06:23,930
and supplies are kept, OK?

1418
01:06:23,930 --> 01:06:29,120
And this is the airlock, or the
 door to the payload bay, OK?

1419
01:06:29,120 --> 01:06:30,740
And Daddy's seat goes here.

1420
01:06:30,740 --> 01:06:32,790
This is where he'll be
 when the shuttle flies.

1421
01:06:32,790 --> 01:06:36,550
Now beside that door,
 which we call the hatch, now,

1422
01:06:36,550 --> 01:06:37,840
can you say that?

1423
01:06:37,840 --> 01:06:38,590
Hatch.

1424
01:06:38,590 --> 01:06:39,620
Right and these are called?

1425
01:06:39,620 --> 01:06:40,850
Lockers.

1426
01:06:40,850 --> 01:06:42,980
Very good.

1427
01:06:42,980 --> 01:06:45,530
I think our genius is
 ready to fly this thing.

1428
01:06:45,530 --> 01:06:46,820
Well, I think so too.

1429
01:06:46,820 --> 01:06:48,900
Maybe we should go
 to the flight deck?

1430
01:06:48,900 --> 01:06:50,550
What do you think?

1431
01:06:50,550 --> 01:06:51,250
Let's go.

1432
01:06:51,250 --> 01:06:51,950
Come on.

1433
01:06:51,950 --> 01:06:53,350
I'm going to go up first, OK?

1434
01:07:03,060 --> 01:07:05,710
Let's go, Champ, come on.

1435
01:07:05,710 --> 01:07:06,790
Here you go.

1436
01:07:06,790 --> 01:07:07,490
I'll tell you what.

1437
01:07:07,490 --> 01:07:10,100
You're going to sit over
 here in the pilot's seat,

1438
01:07:10,100 --> 01:07:11,990
and we're not going to even
 use that poster because I

1439
01:07:11,990 --> 01:07:12,930
don't think you need it.

1440
01:07:12,930 --> 01:07:13,840
What do you think?

1441
01:07:13,840 --> 01:07:14,540
Huh?

1442
01:07:17,430 --> 01:07:19,250
OK?

1443
01:07:19,250 --> 01:07:24,220
Now we're harnessed in,
 there go the main engines,

1444
01:07:24,220 --> 01:07:25,300
and we're leaving the ground.

1445
01:07:25,300 --> 01:07:26,380
Do you it, Reggie?

1446
01:07:26,380 --> 01:07:29,350
Yes, Daddy, I see it.

1447
01:07:29,350 --> 01:07:32,820
Challenger,
 initiate roll program.

1448
01:07:32,820 --> 01:07:34,660
Roger, roll program.

1449
01:07:34,660 --> 01:07:35,690
What do we do now?

1450
01:07:35,690 --> 01:07:37,210
Throttle down.

1451
01:07:37,210 --> 01:07:39,620
Challenger, throttle down.

1452
01:07:39,620 --> 01:07:40,870
Throttle down, Houston.

1453
01:07:40,870 --> 01:07:43,410
Go with throttle
 up, Challenger.

1454
01:07:43,410 --> 01:07:44,920
Roger, throttle up.

1455
01:07:44,920 --> 01:07:47,200
Now the solid rockets.

1456
01:07:47,200 --> 01:07:49,040
SRV separated.

1457
01:07:49,040 --> 01:07:52,860
And now we're
 going into orbit.

1458
01:07:52,860 --> 01:07:54,670
Oh, look, Reggie.

1459
01:07:54,670 --> 01:07:56,290
Look how we're leaving
 the earth behind us.

1460
01:07:56,290 --> 01:07:59,290
Do you see that?

1461
01:07:59,290 --> 01:08:00,860
And now we're going into space.

1462
01:08:05,020 --> 01:08:07,150
Hear how quiet it is?

1463
01:08:07,150 --> 01:08:08,570
Daddy, I hear.

1464
01:08:11,420 --> 01:08:16,400
Oh, look, Reggie,
 we're coming into night.

1465
01:08:16,400 --> 01:08:19,280
Look at all those stars.

1466
01:08:19,280 --> 01:08:23,040
Do you see that, Reggie?

1467
01:08:23,040 --> 01:08:25,470
Yes, Daddy, I see
 millions of them.

1468
01:08:40,350 --> 01:08:42,700
We fly these things
 almost every day

1469
01:08:42,700 --> 01:08:45,190
to keep our skills sharp.

1470
01:08:45,190 --> 01:08:46,690
You don't want any
 rust on you when you're

1471
01:08:46,690 --> 01:08:48,460
about to launch in the shuttle.

1472
01:08:48,460 --> 01:08:50,210
Right, Scobe, I can see that.

1473
01:08:50,210 --> 01:08:52,910
Take it easy now, guys.

1474
01:08:52,910 --> 01:08:54,480
So first of all,
 when we get up there,

1475
01:08:54,480 --> 01:08:56,350
we're going to try some dives
 because I want you to feel

1476
01:08:56,350 --> 01:08:58,570
G-Forces like at liftoff.

1477
01:08:58,570 --> 01:08:59,500
I warn you, Christa.

1478
01:08:59,500 --> 01:09:02,320
This is not going to
 be like airline flying.

1479
01:09:02,320 --> 01:09:04,160
I want to get you
 ready for what you're

1480
01:09:04,160 --> 01:09:06,510
going to experience
 during liftoff and ascent

1481
01:09:06,510 --> 01:09:08,000
and during reentry.

1482
01:09:08,000 --> 01:09:09,050
You ready?

1483
01:09:09,050 --> 01:09:09,750
Ready.

1484
01:09:09,750 --> 01:09:10,450
All right.

1485
01:09:21,060 --> 01:09:24,640
There we go.

1486
01:09:24,640 --> 01:09:28,290
Now, you let me know if anything
 starts loosening up, all right?

1487
01:09:28,290 --> 01:09:30,220
You keep this microphone
 right in front of your mouth

1488
01:09:30,220 --> 01:09:32,270
so we can talk.

1489
01:09:32,270 --> 01:09:34,430
Now your emergency
 oxygen is down there

1490
01:09:34,430 --> 01:09:36,490
and these are the
 different radio bands here,

1491
01:09:36,490 --> 01:09:39,010
and this is a stick that you fly
 with if anything happens to me.

1492
01:10:09,580 --> 01:10:11,130
All right, Christa, here we go.

1493
01:10:18,400 --> 01:10:20,720
(LAUGHING) Wow.

1494
01:10:20,720 --> 01:10:25,400
They say about the T38,
 you keep the dirty side down.

1495
01:10:25,400 --> 01:10:26,680
Oh.

1496
01:10:26,680 --> 01:10:31,120
As you can see, it's just as
 easy to fly her belly side up.

1497
01:10:31,120 --> 01:10:33,140
Want to stay here for a while?

1498
01:10:33,140 --> 01:10:34,450
If it's my choice, Scobe--

1499
01:10:34,450 --> 01:10:35,690
Uh-huh?

1500
01:10:35,690 --> 01:10:38,430
I think I could see
 better right side up.

1501
01:10:38,430 --> 01:10:39,930
All right.

1502
01:10:39,930 --> 01:10:42,190
I'll show you what it feels
 like when we're dropping back

1503
01:10:42,190 --> 01:10:43,960
through the Earth's atmosphere.

1504
01:10:43,960 --> 01:10:46,930
It'll pull your clavicles
 down through your pelvis.

1505
01:10:46,930 --> 01:10:48,100
You ready?

1506
01:10:48,100 --> 01:10:50,680
Probably not actually.

1507
01:10:50,680 --> 01:10:52,980
Here we go.

1508
01:10:52,980 --> 01:10:54,920
Woo hoo hoo.

1509
01:10:54,920 --> 01:10:57,830
Whoa.

1510
01:10:57,830 --> 01:10:59,510
The bottom's dropping out.

1511
01:10:59,510 --> 01:11:00,940
That's bad.

1512
01:11:00,940 --> 01:11:04,330
Hold on to your bottom, Christa,
 you don't want to lose that.

1513
01:11:04,330 --> 01:11:06,700
We'll go back up there now and
 do a couple of other maneuvers

1514
01:11:06,700 --> 01:11:10,970
that'll show you what a
 graceful little bird we're in.

1515
01:11:10,970 --> 01:11:13,100
These are known
 as aileron rolls.

1516
01:11:13,100 --> 01:11:15,660
Once you get the hang of
 them, you can do them all day,

1517
01:11:15,660 --> 01:11:18,060
but the constant turning
 makes some people queasy.

1518
01:11:21,020 --> 01:11:23,480
You're not getting
 queasy, are you, Christa?

1519
01:11:35,080 --> 01:11:36,340
It's yours, Christa.

1520
01:11:36,340 --> 01:11:37,060
My what?

1521
01:11:37,060 --> 01:11:38,940
Your airplane, fly it.

1522
01:11:38,940 --> 01:11:39,640
Fly it?

1523
01:11:39,640 --> 01:11:40,770
Just take control.

1524
01:11:40,770 --> 01:11:41,470
She'll respond.

1525
01:11:44,090 --> 01:11:45,940
Really?

1526
01:11:45,940 --> 01:11:47,250
Absolutely.

1527
01:11:47,250 --> 01:11:48,220
There's planes your friend.

1528
01:11:52,330 --> 01:11:54,040
Oh.

1529
01:11:54,040 --> 01:11:54,740
Wow.

1530
01:11:58,600 --> 01:12:01,170
I have never known
 anything like this.

1531
01:12:01,170 --> 01:12:03,630
Because there isn't
 anything like this.

1532
01:12:03,630 --> 01:12:06,510
Go ahead, get creative.

1533
01:12:06,510 --> 01:12:07,210
I'll try.

1534
01:12:11,310 --> 01:12:13,950
Just something you
 can tell the kids about.

1535
01:12:13,950 --> 01:12:14,810
OK, Scobe.

1536
01:12:32,170 --> 01:12:34,040
Hey, that's pretty good.

1537
01:12:34,040 --> 01:12:36,750
Try it again, to
 the left this time.

1538
01:12:36,750 --> 01:12:37,480
Yes, sir.

1539
01:12:43,300 --> 01:12:45,760
Hey, that was big time.

1540
01:12:45,760 --> 01:12:47,830
Congratulations,
 Airman McAuliffe.

1541
01:12:47,830 --> 01:12:48,610
Watch this.

1542
01:12:52,160 --> 01:12:53,980
Even better.

1543
01:12:53,980 --> 01:12:56,860
Did I earn my wings, Scobe?

1544
01:12:56,860 --> 01:12:59,840
Absolutely, Christa.

1545
01:12:59,840 --> 01:13:03,100
This is what I wanted
 to share with you.

1546
01:13:03,100 --> 01:13:06,320
This is freedom.

1547
01:13:06,320 --> 01:13:09,240
I hope it's something
 you'll remember.

1548
01:13:09,240 --> 01:13:10,090
Oh, Scobe.

1549
01:13:39,060 --> 01:13:42,060
There's just so much to learn.

1550
01:13:42,060 --> 01:13:45,080
The insects and the humidity.

1551
01:13:45,080 --> 01:13:48,280
There's cockroaches
 here you can saddle.

1552
01:13:48,280 --> 01:13:51,330
My hair is constantly frizzled.

1553
01:13:51,330 --> 01:13:52,030
Swell.

1554
01:13:52,030 --> 01:13:54,400
We finally get to talk and
 I fill it with laments.

1555
01:13:54,400 --> 01:13:56,640
Well, you're
 entitled, sweetheart.

1556
01:13:56,640 --> 01:13:57,340
No.

1557
01:13:57,340 --> 01:13:58,550
Don't even listen to me.

1558
01:13:58,550 --> 01:13:59,560
This is ridiculous.

1559
01:13:59,560 --> 01:14:01,980
I'm the most privileged
 person in the United States.

