1850
01:27:45,090 --> 01:27:48,610
Besides it's your turn,
 JR. Who raised you?

1851
01:27:48,610 --> 01:27:49,800
Oh, no you don't.

1852
01:27:49,800 --> 01:27:51,420
Come on, Ron, play.

1853
01:27:51,420 --> 01:27:52,180
Come on, please?

1854
01:27:52,180 --> 01:27:52,880
No.

1855
01:27:52,880 --> 01:27:54,020
Just one more than we'll go.

1856
01:27:54,020 --> 01:27:55,050
You know, you twisted my arm.

1857
01:27:57,820 --> 01:27:59,760
This will be the
 last press opportunity

1858
01:27:59,760 --> 01:28:01,350
as this crew will
 be in quarantine

1859
01:28:01,350 --> 01:28:03,630
between now and the time
 that they leave for the Cape.

1860
01:28:03,630 --> 01:28:06,150
Ladies and gentlemen,
 the crew of STS 51L,

1861
01:28:06,150 --> 01:28:07,540
Dick Scobee Commander.

1862
01:28:23,320 --> 01:28:26,550
OK, Mark, why don't
 we get it started?

1863
01:28:26,550 --> 01:28:30,960
Commander Scobee, what do you
 enjoy most about spaceflight?

1864
01:28:30,960 --> 01:28:32,850
Oh.

1865
01:28:32,850 --> 01:28:34,780
All of it, I guess.

1866
01:28:34,780 --> 01:28:36,570
In particular, now
 there is a launch

1867
01:28:36,570 --> 01:28:38,490
with all that
 associated machinery

1868
01:28:38,490 --> 01:28:41,730
