 need everything we got.

2075
01:38:34,330 --> 01:38:36,010
Better put the ice
 team on a special alert.

2076
01:38:36,010 --> 01:38:37,810
Right.

2077
01:38:37,810 --> 01:38:39,340
What do we got
 from the contractors?

2078
01:38:39,340 --> 01:38:41,110
Anybody say how this
 freeze is going to affect

2079
01:38:41,110 --> 01:38:42,450
the principle systems?

2080
01:38:42,450 --> 01:38:43,150
Nothing yet.

2081
01:38:46,970 --> 01:38:50,680
Any other element in the solid
 rockets this cold will affect?

2082
01:38:50,680 --> 01:38:54,230
Oh, I think the
 O-rings is the main one.

2083
01:38:54,230 --> 01:38:57,080
The O-rings are made of rubber
 and rubber is affected by cold,

2084
01:38:57,080 --> 01:38:59,330
so we know we've got
 some kind of problem.

2085
01:38:59,330 --> 01:39:01,830
How much of a
 problem, we can't tell.

2086
01:39:01,830 --> 01:39:04,780
We don't have enough data.

2087
01:39:04,780 --> 01:39:06,720
No tests have ever
 been run on the O-rings

2088
01:39:06,720 --> 01:39:09,490
at temperatures that low.

2089
01:39:09,490 --> 01:39:12,560
I want to get Marshall
 in on this right away.

2090
01:39:12,560 --> 01:39:14,900
Let's get Cecil Houston to
 arrange a telephone conference

2091
01:39:14,900 --> 01:39:17,300
between us and the Marshall
 engineers both down at Kennedy

2092
01:39:17,300 --> 01:39:18,980
and at Huntsville.

2093
01:39:18,980 --> 01:39:22,070
This problem could
 definitely affect the launch.

2094
01:39:22,070 --> 01:39:26,240
Ladies and gentlemen,
 this is a diamond stylus.

2095
01:39:26,240 --> 01:39:29,060
This is a magnum of champagne.

2096
01:39:29,060 --> 01:39:33,930
We're going to carve on
 the one with the other.

2097
01:39:33,930 --> 01:39:36,200
Then what are we going to
 do, put it in a time capsule?

2098
01:39:36,200 --> 01:39:38,900
Oh, no, no, no, everyone
 gets to carve their name on it,

2099
01:39:38,900 --> 01:39:40,310
and then when we're
 back home in Houston,

2100
01:39:40,310 --> 01:39:43,220
we have one hell of a party
 and this bottle of champagne

2101
01:39:43,220 --> 01:39:44,090
gets to kick it off.

2102
01:39:44,090 --> 01:39:44,790
All right.

2103
01:39:54,190 --> 01:39:57,230
Nobody reporting launch
 violations due to the cold?

2104
01:39:57,230 --> 01:39:58,900
Not yet, Horace.

2105
01:39:58,900 --> 01:40:00,140
Kind of hard to believe.

2106
01:40:00,140 --> 01:40:01,720
Is tomorrow definite?

2107
01:40:01,720 --> 01:40:04,150
As definite as we can
 be with this weather.

2108
01:40:04,150 --> 01:40:06,130
Well, looking at the
 predictions for tonight,

2109
01:40:06,130 --> 01:40:07,450
you could have a delay.

2110
01:40:07,450 --> 01:40:08,800
If there's another
 scrub, how will

2111
01:40:08,800 --> 01:40:10,960
that affect future flights?

2112
01:40:10,960 --> 01:40:12,640
We're planning on
 launching tomorrow.

2113
01:40:12,640 --> 01:40:16,090
If there's a delay, we'll
 deal with it as we always do.

2114
01:40:16,090 --> 01:40:18,460
Aren't you getting tight
 for the March 6 launch?

2115
01:40:18,460 --> 01:40:19,810
Our schedule is always tight.

2116
01:40:19,810 --> 01:40:20,680
We're used to tight.

2117
01:40:20,680 --> 01:40:22,480
But to have any hope of
 keeping the schedule you've

2118
01:40:22,480 --> 01:40:25,420
announced for 1986, don't
 you have to get Challenger

2119
01:40:25,420 --> 01:40:27,160
off within the next two days?

2120
01:40:27,160 --> 01:40:28,630
No, that isn't exactly so.

2121
01:40:28,630 --> 01:40:30,780
Well, we know the March
 6 launch can't be moved,

2122
01:40:30,780 --> 01:40:31,480
so how are you--

2123
01:40:31,480 --> 01:40:33,880
I want to be perfectly
 clear about something.

2124
01:40:33,880 --> 01:40:36,730
The decision to launch
 Challenger or any other orbiter

2125
01:40:36,730 --> 01:40:39,550
will not be influenced
 by schedule pressure.

2126
01:40:39,550 --> 01:40:42,520
We'll sit on the ground until
 we believe it's safe to go.

2127
01:40:42,520 --> 01:40:45,120
The safety of the
 crew and the orbiter

2128
01:40:45,120 --> 01:40:46,750
will be the sole criterion.

2129
01:40:51,340 --> 01:40:53,140
This is Cecil, Houston.

2130
01:40:53,140 --> 01:40:55,720
I think we have
 everyone connected.

2131
01:40:55,720 --> 01:40:57,010
Can you all hear me?

2132
01:40:57,010 --> 01:40:57,990
Yes.

2133
01:40:57,990 --> 01:40:58,710
Yeah.

2134
01:40:58,710 --> 01:40:59,410
Yes.

2135
01:40:59,410 --> 01:41:01,510
Morton-Thiokol has
 some concerns about

2136
01:41:01,510 --> 01:41:03,100
the effect the cold
 weather might have

2137
01:41:03,100 --> 01:41:05,120
on the solid rocket boosters.

2138
01:41:05,120 --> 01:41:07,060
So let's get started.

2139
01:41:07,060 --> 01:41:09,270
Morton-Thiokol, do you
 want to kick it off?

2140
01:41:09,270 --> 01:41:10,370
I will.

2141
01:41:10,370 --> 01:41:11,660
I've got a question.

2142
01:41:11,660 --> 01:41:14,260
I keep getting this
 boomerfest every time.

2143
01:41:14,260 --> 01:41:17,110
Wait a minute, I'm
 getting a voice delay.

2144
01:41:17,110 --> 01:41:19,230
Maybe if you talk
 a little slower.

2145
01:41:19,230 --> 01:41:21,960
All right, let's try it again.

2146
01:41:21,960 --> 01:41:23,460
Go ahead, Judson.

2147
01:41:23,460 --> 01:41:26,340
What did you guys at
 Morton-Thiokol come up with?

2148
01:41:26,340 --> 01:41:28,820
Will these low temperatures
 affect the performance

2149
01:41:28,820 --> 01:41:30,570
of the solid rockets?

2150
01:41:30,570 --> 01:41:32,520
We've been working
 on it, Judson.

2151
01:41:32,520 --> 01:41:33,840
There's really no
 experience base

2152
01:41:33,840 --> 01:41:35,430
for that kind of
 low temperature,

2153
01:41:35,430 --> 01:41:36,750
but it does look
 like there could

2154
01:41:36,750 --> 01:41:39,470
be serious problems in
 launching in this kind of cold.

2155
01:41:39,470 --> 01:41:41,370
Can you give us
 some specifics?

2156
01:41:41,370 --> 01:41:44,150
I lost it after what he
 about serious problems.

2157
01:41:44,150 --> 01:41:45,890
I keep hearing my own
 voice coming back at me.

2158
01:41:45,890 --> 01:41:46,590
Wait.

2159
01:41:46,590 --> 01:41:47,290
Wait.

2160
01:41:47,290 --> 01:41:49,920
We didn't get that, Stan.

2161
01:41:49,920 --> 01:41:51,610
We're not getting
 anywhere with this.

2162
01:41:51,610 --> 01:41:53,610
The problem is we're
 on a two wire system that

2163
01:41:53,610 --> 01:41:56,120
can't carry this much traffic.

2164
01:41:56,120 --> 01:41:58,660
We're going to have to go out to
 the marshall office at Kennedy,

2165
01:41:58,660 --> 01:42:01,650
use the telecom system
 they got set up out there.

2166
01:42:01,650 --> 01:42:03,290
You all stay right
 where you are.

2167
01:42:03,290 --> 01:42:05,200
Set to separate.

2168
01:42:05,200 --> 01:42:06,630
That OK with everybody?

2169
01:42:06,630 --> 01:42:07,490
Yeah.

2170
01:42:07,490 --> 01:42:08,190
Yes.

2171
01:42:08,190 --> 01:42:09,330
OK, I'll be here.

2172
01:42:15,330 --> 01:42:16,240
Look at that.

2173
01:42:19,060 --> 01:42:22,540
Well, I think it's
 about that time, folks.

2174
01:42:22,540 --> 01:42:24,760
Yeah, it's time for the families
 to head on home, because

2175
01:42:24,760 --> 01:42:27,760
from this point on, I want the
 crew to be thinking of nothing

2176
01:42:27,760 --> 01:42:28,780
but the mission, all right?

2177
01:42:28,780 --> 01:42:29,940
Nobody's going home.

2178
01:42:29,940 --> 01:42:33,130
There are parties here in
 Titusville, parties in Orlando.

2179
01:42:33,130 --> 01:42:35,640
We have three bus
 loads of our own.

2180
01:42:35,640 --> 01:42:36,340
Y'all have fun.

2181
01:42:36,340 --> 01:42:38,680
I'll be in much more of a
 party mood when I get back.

2182
01:42:38,680 --> 01:42:39,830
I'll see you in a week, hon.

2183
01:42:39,830 --> 01:42:42,800
OK.

2184
01:42:42,800 --> 01:42:43,560
I did it.

2185
01:42:43,560 --> 01:42:44,640
Your thesis?

2186
01:42:44,640 --> 01:42:45,340
Yeah.

2187
01:42:45,340 --> 01:42:47,590
When the flight got delayed,
 I called the university

2188
01:42:47,590 --> 01:42:49,900
and they said if I mailed
 it before the launch

2189
01:42:49,900 --> 01:42:51,670
that they would give
 me my degree in orbit.

2190
01:42:51,670 --> 01:42:53,950
The first degree
 awarded in space.

2191
01:42:53,950 --> 01:42:56,860
Greg, this is inspiring.

2192
01:42:56,860 --> 01:42:59,440
Well, you've got to get it
 to Hughes by tomorrow morning

2193
01:42:59,440 --> 01:43:02,000
so they can type it up and
 take it over to the university.

2194
01:43:02,000 --> 01:43:05,100
Oh, it'll be
 there first thing.

2195
01:43:05,100 --> 01:43:06,990
There ought to be
 something momentous to say.

2196
01:43:06,990 --> 01:43:08,910
Like what?

2197
01:43:08,910 --> 01:43:11,540
There's nothing that we
 need to say to each other.

2198
01:43:11,540 --> 01:43:14,730
Well, something better than
 see you in a week, honey.

2199
01:43:14,730 --> 01:43:16,190
I'll see you in
 a week sounds good.

2200
01:43:16,190 --> 01:43:18,790
Hits it on the head.

2201
01:43:18,790 --> 01:43:21,270
Well, catch some
 stardust for me, will ya?

2202
01:43:24,940 --> 01:43:25,710
All I can hold.

2203
01:43:30,800 --> 01:43:31,670
See ya in a week, honey.

2204
01:43:38,140 --> 01:43:41,630
Oh, thank you.

2205
01:43:41,630 --> 01:43:43,310
You look for me and
 the kids tomorrow, OK?

2206
01:43:43,310 --> 01:43:45,050
We'll be the ones waving.

2207
01:43:45,050 --> 01:43:47,230
I'll spot you.

2208
01:43:47,230 --> 01:43:48,290
The kids OK?

2209
01:43:48,290 --> 01:43:49,260
Oh, they're fine.

2210
01:43:49,260 --> 01:43:50,120
Fine.

2211
01:43:50,120 --> 01:43:51,750
They're excited.

2212
01:43:51,750 --> 01:43:55,120
I told them I'd take them to
 Disney World if you didn't go,

2213
01:43:55,120 --> 01:43:56,540
but I have a feeling
 you're going to go.

2214
01:43:56,540 --> 01:43:59,680
I think you'll
 finally be up there.

2215
01:43:59,680 --> 01:44:02,000
I love you, sweetheart.

2216
01:44:02,000 --> 01:44:03,630
I love you, sweetheart.

2217
01:44:06,270 --> 01:44:07,970
And I love you
 and the kids more

2218
01:44:07,970 --> 01:44:09,500
than anything on this earth.

2219
01:44:15,420 --> 01:44:17,530
I'll pull out
 the nightstand now.

2220
01:44:17,530 --> 01:44:18,760
Quiet.

2221
01:44:18,760 --> 01:44:19,890
You take care, OK?

2222
01:44:19,890 --> 01:44:20,590
Kiss for the kids.

2223
01:44:20,590 --> 01:44:22,420
OK, bye.

2224
01:44:22,420 --> 01:44:23,430
Bye.

2225
01:44:23,430 --> 01:44:24,130
Watch it.

2226
01:44:24,130 --> 01:44:24,940
This is Janelle's.

2227
01:44:24,940 --> 01:44:26,110
She doesn't like her swea--

2228
01:44:32,370 --> 01:44:35,770
Some swell time for you
 to get romantic, eh, you.

2229
01:44:35,770 --> 01:44:37,690
You want to hang around?

2230
01:44:37,690 --> 01:44:40,380
I want you to hang around.

2231
01:44:40,380 --> 01:44:42,290
I'm going to throw away
 your roller skates.

2232
01:44:48,560 --> 01:44:49,560
OK, bye.

2233
01:44:59,040 --> 01:45:00,070
Cecil Houston.

2234
01:45:00,070 --> 01:45:01,170
This is the Coast Guard.

2235
01:45:01,170 --> 01:45:01,870
Yes, sir.

2236
01:45:01,870 --> 01:45:03,670
What can I do for
 the Coast Guard?

2237
01:45:03,670 --> 01:45:06,070
We're in communication with
 your two recovery vessels,

2238
01:45:06,070 --> 01:45:07,690
the ones that will pick
 up the solid rocket

2239
01:45:07,690 --> 01:45:09,300
boosters after launch tomorrow.

2240
01:45:09,300 --> 01:45:10,000
Yes.

2241
01:45:10,000 --> 01:45:12,690
They're on station 120
 miles due east of here.

2242
01:45:12,690 --> 01:45:13,390
Right.

2243
01:45:13,390 --> 01:45:14,670
That's right.

2244
01:45:14,670 --> 01:45:16,210
They're in a full
 gale out there.

2245
01:45:16,210 --> 01:45:17,800
Captain Devlin says
 he's never been

2246
01:45:17,800 --> 01:45:19,840
in conditions like these
 outside of a hurricane

2247
01:45:19,840 --> 01:45:21,370
in the North Atlantic.

2248
01:45:21,370 --> 01:45:25,270
50 knot winds, extended
 gusts holding at 72 knots,

2249
01:45:25,270 --> 01:45:27,430
waves 30 feet high.

2250
01:45:27,430 --> 01:45:30,700
Those are shallow draft
 vessels and they're in survival

2251
01:45:30,700 --> 01:45:32,920
mode heading back to Houston.

2252
01:45:32,920 --> 01:45:35,400
The thing is, they won't be on
 station to retrieve the rockets

2253
01:45:35,400 --> 01:45:36,940
if you launch in the morning.

2254
01:45:36,940 --> 01:45:40,130
Don't know if that will
 affect your plans or not.

2255
01:45:40,130 --> 01:45:41,590
No, I did get your
 message, Christa.

2256
01:45:41,590 --> 01:45:43,510
I was sorry not to have
 a chance to say goodbye

2257
01:45:43,510 --> 01:45:45,730
so I'm glad you called again.

2258
01:45:45,730 --> 01:45:48,880
I called because I thought
 about our discussions, Bob,

2259
01:45:48,880 --> 01:45:54,290
and I really do think you all
 created a beautiful experiment.

2260
01:45:54,290 --> 01:45:57,220
I had to become a student
 again to appreciate it.

2261
01:45:57,220 --> 01:46:01,570
I just wanted to say that
 and I wanted to thank you.

2262
01:46:01,570 --> 01:46:02,370
That's great, Christa.

2263
01:46:02,370 --> 01:46:03,260
I'll tell everybody.

2264
01:46:03,260 --> 01:46:03,960
I hope you will.

2265
01:46:03,960 --> 01:46:05,170
It'll mean a lot to me.

2266
01:46:05,170 --> 01:46:06,970
It'll mean a lot to them.

2267
01:46:06,970 --> 01:46:10,080
Say, did I sound like a
 Texan when I said y'all?

2268
01:46:10,080 --> 01:46:10,780
There you go.

2269
01:46:10,780 --> 01:46:13,900
Now you're talking English.

2270
01:46:13,900 --> 01:46:16,240
Listen, have a
 good trip, Christa.

2271
01:46:16,240 --> 01:46:18,700
I think we all had a chance to
 become students again and learn

2272
01:46:18,700 --> 01:46:20,560
something from each other.

2273
01:46:20,560 --> 01:46:22,330
I know I'm speaking for
 everybody here when I say

2274
01:46:22,330 --> 01:46:24,280
we'll be thinking about you.

2275
01:46:24,280 --> 01:46:27,090
I'll carry that with me.

2276
01:46:27,090 --> 01:46:28,700
See you when I get back, Bob.

2277
01:46:28,700 --> 01:46:30,480
All right.

2278
01:46:30,480 --> 01:46:31,610
Bye.

2279
01:46:31,610 --> 01:46:32,320
Bye bye.

2280
01:46:38,000 --> 01:46:40,620
This is Cecil Houston.

2281
01:46:40,620 --> 01:46:42,530
I think everybody's hooked up.

2282
01:46:42,530 --> 01:46:44,390
I want to say first
 that the boost recovery

2283
01:46:44,390 --> 01:46:46,610
vessels are fighting a hell
 of a gale about 100 miles

2284
01:46:46,610 --> 01:46:48,440
out to sea.

2285
01:46:48,440 --> 01:46:49,710
Soon as this telecom
 is over, I'll

2286
01:46:49,710 --> 01:46:51,050
have to see if
 Arnie Aldrich wants

2287
01:46:51,050 --> 01:46:54,580
to launch without those
 vessels on station.

2288
01:46:54,580 --> 01:46:57,960
OK, Bob Lund, why
 don't you start?

2289
01:46:57,960 --> 01:46:59,480
This is Joe Kilminster.

2290
01:46:59,480 --> 01:47:01,460
Earlier today, we were
 informed about the extremely

2291
01:47:01,460 --> 01:47:04,670
low temperatures predicted
 for tomorrow morning's launch.

2292
01:47:04,670 --> 01:47:05,900
The main question
 we're looking at

2293
01:47:05,900 --> 01:47:07,790
is how the O-rings in
 the solid rocket booster

2294
01:47:07,790 --> 01:47:08,950
would be affected.

2295
01:47:08,950 --> 01:47:11,030
Now we put together some
 charts with information

2296
01:47:11,030 --> 01:47:12,290
from previous flights.

2297
01:47:12,290 --> 01:47:15,990
We'll go over those and then
 make our recommendations.

2298
01:47:15,990 --> 01:47:17,360
Give us a minute, will ya?

2299
01:47:17,360 --> 01:47:21,630
The charts are just
 coming over the fax now.

2300
01:47:21,630 --> 01:47:23,120
Yeah, that's fine.

2301
01:47:23,120 --> 01:47:24,500
Sorry about the delay.

2302
01:47:24,500 --> 01:47:27,270
Arnie Thompson
 and Roger Boisjoly

2303
01:47:27,270 --> 01:47:28,250
have been doing the research.

2304
01:47:28,250 --> 01:47:29,580
They'll make the presentation.

2305
01:47:29,580 --> 01:47:30,280
Arnie?

2306
01:47:33,460 --> 01:47:38,590
We have no data on O-rings
 operating at temperatures this

2307
01:47:38,590 --> 01:47:42,520
low, but we've put
 together a rationale based

2308
01:47:42,520 --> 01:47:44,620
on the information we have.

2309
01:47:44,620 --> 01:47:49,000
The charts are mostly not
 typed, so if there's a problem

2310
01:47:49,000 --> 01:47:51,510
reading them, let us know.

2311
01:47:51,510 --> 01:47:53,270
I'll begin by
 citing flight 15,

2312
01:47:53,270 --> 01:47:54,650
which was launched a year ago.

2313
01:47:54,650 --> 01:47:55,880
The temperature
 at that launch was

2314
01:47:55,880 --> 01:48:00,290
53 degrees, which is the coldest
 reading experience to date.

2315
01:48:00,290 --> 01:48:02,720
We're faxing a chart now
 that shows the O-ring erosion

2316
01:48:02,720 --> 01:48:04,610
on that flight.

2317
01:48:04,610 --> 01:48:05,800
Any questions so far?

2318
01:48:05,800 --> 01:48:06,500
Go ahead.

2319
01:48:06,500 --> 01:48:09,020
We've got the chart
 coming through.

2320
01:48:09,020 --> 01:48:12,530
The Air Force estimates 29
 degrees at launch tomorrow

2321
01:48:12,530 --> 01:48:13,730
morning.

2322
01:48:13,730 --> 01:48:15,860
That is far below any
 temperature we've launched

2323
01:48:15,860 --> 01:48:19,430
with before, so determining
 if this extreme cold

2324
01:48:19,430 --> 01:48:24,830
will affect the O-rings, and if
 it does, how much, is critical.

2325
01:48:24,830 --> 01:48:28,490
The chart you're
 getting relate to that.

2326
01:48:28,490 --> 01:48:31,490
The indication is that
 the cold hardened O-rings

2327
01:48:31,490 --> 01:48:33,470
will be slower in sealing.

2328
01:48:33,470 --> 01:48:35,240
Therefore, there could
 be hot gas leakage

2329
01:48:35,240 --> 01:48:37,880
past the primary
