 rationale together

2577
02:00:04,620 --> 02:00:05,690
pretty quick about the launch.

2578
02:00:05,690 --> 02:00:06,390
Roger.

2579
02:00:06,390 --> 02:00:09,000
Now just give me your
 assessment of the situation.

2580
02:00:09,000 --> 02:00:10,500
I've got the details
 on the monitors,

2581
02:00:10,500 --> 02:00:12,060
but it doesn't tell me--

2582
02:00:12,060 --> 02:00:14,540
it doesn't give me
 an overall picture.

2583
02:00:14,540 --> 02:00:16,140
It's grim, Horace.

2584
02:00:16,140 --> 02:00:18,670
Here at the joint of 35 foot
 level, there's ice everywhere.

2585
02:00:18,670 --> 02:00:20,370
This metal grating
 that I'm standing on

2586
02:00:20,370 --> 02:00:21,990
is one solid sheet of ice.

2587
02:00:21,990 --> 02:00:22,770
OK.

2588
02:00:22,770 --> 02:00:25,150
Work your way down to
 the 195 foot level.

2589
02:00:25,150 --> 02:00:26,250
See what it's like
 where the crew

2590
02:00:26,250 --> 02:00:27,420
will be walking to the orbiter.

2591
02:00:51,720 --> 02:00:55,200
[PHONE RINGING]

2592
02:00:59,670 --> 02:01:00,900
Hello?

2593
02:01:00,900 --> 02:01:03,730
Well, did you get the flowers?

2594
02:01:03,730 --> 02:01:05,980
What did you do,
 win the lottery?

2595
02:01:05,980 --> 02:01:07,590
Scobee probably did
 something like that,

2596
02:01:07,590 --> 02:01:09,770
and I didn't want to
 look bad in comparison.

2597
02:01:09,770 --> 02:01:13,160
Oh, El, they're
 absolutely beautiful.

2598
02:01:13,160 --> 02:01:16,440
Oh, how can somebody
 screw things up so bad

2599
02:01:16,440 --> 02:01:18,690
and then unscrew them up, huh?

2600
02:01:18,690 --> 02:01:22,380
What's somebody supposed to
 do with you, country boy?

2601
02:01:22,380 --> 02:01:26,400
I got an idea, but you
 probably wouldn't like it.

2602
02:01:26,400 --> 02:01:28,410
I think we should
 take a vacation.

2603
02:01:28,410 --> 02:01:29,720
Man, that's a horrible idea.

2604
02:01:29,720 --> 02:01:30,610
Think of something else.

2605
02:01:30,610 --> 02:01:31,310
[KNOCKING]

2606
02:01:31,310 --> 02:01:33,330
Come on, El, curfew.

2607
02:01:33,330 --> 02:01:34,560
I've got to go.

2608
02:01:34,560 --> 02:01:36,360
I'll see you in a week, honey.

2609
02:01:36,360 --> 02:01:37,360
OK, bye.

2610
02:01:43,700 --> 02:01:46,280
At the 195 foot
 level here, there's

2611
02:01:46,280 --> 02:01:48,970
extensive sheet ice
 between the elevator

2612
02:01:48,970 --> 02:01:50,720
where the crew will
 emerge and the escape

2613
02:01:50,720 --> 02:01:51,760
baskets on the west side.

2614
02:01:51,760 --> 02:01:52,460
You see it?

2615
02:01:52,460 --> 02:01:54,080
Yeah, got it in closeup.

2616
02:01:54,080 --> 02:01:55,400
If the crew had
 to be evacuated,

2617
02:01:55,400 --> 02:01:57,020
they'd have to run
 across that ice.

2618
02:01:57,020 --> 02:01:58,360
It's very slippery, Horace.

2619
02:01:58,360 --> 02:02:00,580
They'd have a problem.

2620
02:02:00,580 --> 02:02:02,300
What about the handrails?

2621
02:02:02,300 --> 02:02:03,890
There's ice all over that too.

2622
02:02:03,890 --> 02:02:05,160
Long icicles hanging down.

2623
02:02:05,160 --> 02:02:06,560
There's a hell of a
 lot of ice everywhere.

2624
02:02:06,560 --> 02:02:08,020
That's a simple fact.

2625
02:02:08,020 --> 02:02:09,590
Can you see the impact
 of this on your monitor?

2626
02:02:09,590 --> 02:02:10,350
I get it.

2627
02:02:10,350 --> 02:02:13,110
The closeups look like
 something out of Dr. Zhivago.

2628
02:02:13,110 --> 02:02:14,960
Now the big problem
 is the massive ice

2629
02:02:14,960 --> 02:02:16,760
on the whole structure.

2630
02:02:16,760 --> 02:02:18,980
What's going to happen when
 those rockets light off and all

2631
02:02:18,980 --> 02:02:20,600
that ice gets shook loose?

2632
02:02:20,600 --> 02:02:23,960
I'd say the only choice you have
 today, Horace, is not to go.

2633
02:02:23,960 --> 02:02:25,250
All right, Charlie,
 come on back in.

2634
02:04:40,670 --> 02:04:45,410
We are now at T minus 4
 hours 12 minutes and counting.

2635
02:04:45,410 --> 02:04:48,050
Weather prediction at the
 moment is clear for launch

2636
02:04:48,050 --> 02:04:50,780
with acceptable winds aloft.

2637
02:04:50,780 --> 02:04:52,940
Still concern however
 about the cold temperatures

2638
02:04:52,940 --> 02:04:54,890
and whether they'll violate
 the launch commit criteria.

2639
02:04:59,890 --> 02:05:00,660
Morning, Mr. Aldrich.

2640
02:05:00,660 --> 02:05:02,970
Morning.

2641
02:05:02,970 --> 02:05:05,200
Small news, but
 good news, Arnie.

2642
02:05:05,200 --> 02:05:07,600
The ice on the side of the
 gantry facing the orbiter

2643
02:05:07,600 --> 02:05:09,060
is starting to melt.

2644
02:05:09,060 --> 02:05:11,770
That's better, but
 we're still a long way

2645
02:05:11,770 --> 02:05:13,520
from out of the woods.

2646
02:05:13,520 --> 02:05:15,130
We just might be all
 right by launch time.

2647
02:05:21,590 --> 02:05:24,150
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

2648
02:05:43,330 --> 02:05:44,030
Right.

2649
02:05:44,030 --> 02:05:46,050
We'll keep monitoring
 that and call

2650
02:05:46,050 --> 02:05:49,030
me back is anything changes.

2651
02:05:49,030 --> 02:05:52,380
If the south side of
 the gap is clear of ice,

2652
02:05:52,380 --> 02:05:54,570
we could be looking pretty good.

2653
02:05:54,570 --> 02:05:56,850
Well, we'll look
 at it real careful.

2654
02:05:56,850 --> 02:05:58,040
Looking better now though.

2655
02:06:03,890 --> 02:06:06,210
Now you take very
 good care of my stuff.

2656
02:06:06,210 --> 02:06:07,400
My football tickets
 are in there.

2657
02:06:07,400 --> 02:06:08,100
Sure.

2658
02:06:08,100 --> 02:06:10,950
In case of an abort, I'll fly
 them to you personally, Scobe.

2659
02:06:10,950 --> 02:06:12,750
What is your primary
 abort site, Dakar?

2660
02:06:12,750 --> 02:06:13,560
Uh-huh.

2661
02:06:13,560 --> 02:06:15,030
Well, due to the
 cold, you'll probably

2662
02:06:15,030 --> 02:06:16,140
have considerable hold time.

2663
02:06:16,140 --> 02:06:18,440
Might even have lift
 off close to noon.

2664
02:06:18,440 --> 02:06:20,190
Well, one thing we
 know how to do is hold.

2665
02:06:20,190 --> 02:06:20,890
Right.

2666
02:06:32,400 --> 02:06:35,150
Hey, Christa, how do you feel?

2667
02:06:35,150 --> 02:06:35,850
I feel great.

2668
02:06:52,380 --> 02:06:53,750
Everybody call home?

2669
02:06:53,750 --> 02:06:55,320
Yes, teacher.

2670
02:06:55,320 --> 02:06:57,960
Imagine all the people who
 came to Florida for a vacation

2671
02:06:57,960 --> 02:07:00,190
and are going home
 with frostbite.

2672
02:07:00,190 --> 02:07:02,910
A personal note, folks, if
 you need to use the toilet,

2673
02:07:02,910 --> 02:07:05,190
I suggest you use the one at
 the bottom of the building.

2674
02:07:05,190 --> 02:07:09,570
The stairs to the crew
 lavatory are blocked by ice.

2675
02:07:09,570 --> 02:07:12,120
I've decided I'm not going
 till I'm back on Earth.

2676
02:07:30,320 --> 02:07:32,330
T minus one hour.

2677
02:07:32,330 --> 02:07:34,220
Everything continues to
 look favorable for an on

2678
02:07:34,220 --> 02:07:35,770
time launch of the 51L mission.

2679
02:07:54,170 --> 02:07:55,780
My kind of weather.

2680
02:07:55,780 --> 02:07:57,540
We've got a
 beautiful day to fly.

2681
02:07:57,540 --> 02:07:58,550
A little cold thought, Dick.

2682
02:07:58,550 --> 02:07:59,900
Nah, that's good.

2683
02:07:59,900 --> 02:08:00,720
It's OK.

2684
02:08:19,120 --> 02:08:19,950
All right?

2685
02:08:19,950 --> 02:08:20,650
Ready?

2686
02:08:20,650 --> 02:08:21,350
Thank you.

2687
02:08:28,440 --> 02:08:31,980
OK, take it easy.

2688
02:08:31,980 --> 02:08:32,730
See you in a week.

2689
02:09:11,400 --> 02:09:12,180
Have a good flight.

2690
02:09:16,370 --> 02:09:17,160
See you up there, El.

2691
02:09:17,160 --> 02:09:17,860
Bye.

2692
02:09:36,790 --> 02:09:38,500
Get your feet through?

2693
02:09:38,500 --> 02:09:39,200
OK.

2694
02:09:49,490 --> 02:09:50,730
You're gonna need a haircut.

2695
02:10:05,630 --> 02:10:08,430
Well, next time I see
 you, we'll be in space.

2696
02:10:08,430 --> 02:10:09,130
Right.

2697
02:10:23,490 --> 02:10:27,140
I've got a present for you.

2698
02:10:27,140 --> 02:10:28,530
It's an apple.

2699
02:10:28,530 --> 02:10:29,230
Johnny.

2700
02:10:31,880 --> 02:10:33,290
Thank you.

2701
02:10:33,290 --> 02:10:33,990
Save it for me.

2702
02:10:33,990 --> 02:10:35,480
I'll eat it when I get back.

2703
02:10:35,480 --> 02:10:37,460
It'll be waiting
 right here for you.

2704
02:10:37,460 --> 02:10:39,240
Bye.

2705
02:10:39,240 --> 02:10:40,310
Greg, morning.
 - Great.

2706
02:10:40,310 --> 02:10:41,010
Morning.

2707
02:10:41,010 --> 02:10:42,610
It looks like you're
 really going to go today.

2708
02:10:42,610 --> 02:10:44,010
I sure hope so.

2709
02:10:44,010 --> 02:10:46,390
T minus 50 minutes.

2710
02:10:46,390 --> 02:10:49,050
Pilot Michael J. Smith has
 been asked by the orbiter test

2711
02:10:49,050 --> 02:10:52,140
conductor to configure switches
 in the cockpit to preactivate

2712
02:10:52,140 --> 02:10:55,570
the water spray boilers.

2713
02:10:55,570 --> 02:10:56,270
That's good.

2714
02:11:07,000 --> 02:11:07,700
See ya.

2715
02:11:32,080 --> 02:11:35,810
Scobe, the resetting we talked
 about, save that for the hold.

2716
02:11:35,810 --> 02:11:38,030
It's coming up in a
 couple of minutes.

2717
02:11:38,030 --> 02:11:39,820
And, Mike, you can
 start yours now.

2718
02:11:56,810 --> 02:11:58,120
This will be the
 first of two planned

2719
02:11:58,120 --> 02:12:02,190
holds remaining before
 the launch of mission 51L.

2720
02:12:02,190 --> 02:12:03,490
You've done this
 before, haven't you?

2721
02:12:03,490 --> 02:12:06,550
Well, maybe once or twice.

2722
02:12:06,550 --> 02:12:07,250
Thank you.

2723
02:12:35,230 --> 02:12:35,930
Thank you.

2724
02:12:52,350 --> 02:12:53,760
Hey, Reggie, come on in here.

2725
02:12:53,760 --> 02:12:54,560
How you doing?

2726
02:12:54,560 --> 02:12:55,320
Hi, Cheryl.

2727
02:12:55,320 --> 02:12:56,020
How are you?

2728
02:13:00,180 --> 02:13:01,920
Lorna, make me some coffee.

2729
02:13:01,920 --> 02:13:02,620
OK.

2730
02:13:02,620 --> 02:13:03,360
Black.

2731
02:13:03,360 --> 02:13:04,060
Right.

2732
02:13:10,470 --> 02:13:14,100
Gosh, I hope
 that's not an omen.

2733
02:13:14,100 --> 02:13:16,070
Jane.

2734
02:13:16,070 --> 02:13:18,450
Launch sequencer has started
 retracting the orbiter crew

2735
02:13:18,450 --> 02:13:21,270
access arm, which is the
 walkway used by the astronauts

2736
02:13:21,270 --> 02:13:22,200
to climb in the vehicle.

2737
02:13:22,200 --> 02:13:24,410
I'm going to make voice
 contact with each of you.

2738
02:13:24,410 --> 02:13:26,540
OK, Judy, say something, please.

2739
02:13:26,540 --> 02:13:29,530
Cowabunga.

2740
02:13:29,530 --> 02:13:31,950
Cowabunga, what's that?

2741
02:13:31,950 --> 02:13:33,630
That's how cold it is in here.

2742
02:13:40,070 --> 02:13:40,770
Still no danger.

2743
02:13:40,770 --> 02:13:42,420
It's ice cold up
 in the solid rocket

2744
02:13:42,420 --> 02:13:44,650
that's violate launch
 commit criteria.

2745
02:13:44,650 --> 02:13:46,480
On the other hand, the ice
 on the launch pad structures

2746
02:13:46,480 --> 02:13:47,750
is still there.

2747
02:13:47,750 --> 02:13:49,720
So the problem
 is could that ice

2748
02:13:49,720 --> 02:13:51,980
get involved with the
 orbiter when we blast off?

2749
02:13:51,980 --> 02:13:52,930
Right.

2750
02:13:52,930 --> 02:13:54,510
Of course, you got
 a warm sun now.

2751
02:13:54,510 --> 02:13:56,920
There's considerable
 melting going on.

2752
02:13:56,920 --> 02:13:58,730
That's helping things.

2753
02:13:58,730 --> 02:14:00,160
I sure don't want
 to see those icicles

2754
02:14:00,160 --> 02:14:02,650
turned into flying missiles.

2755
02:14:02,650 --> 02:14:05,800
Let me get one more
 recommendation from the pad.

2756
02:14:05,800 --> 02:14:08,710
We are at T minus 20
 minutes and counting.

2757
02:14:08,710 --> 02:14:10,930
Purge of the orbiter's
 fuel cells is now underway,

2758
02:14:10,930 --> 02:14:13,240
and the data processing
 engineer has confirmed

2759
02:14:13,240 --> 02:14:15,310
the onboard computers
 are in the process

2760
02:14:15,310 --> 02:14:17,110
of making the transition
 to the terminal

2761
02:14:17,110 --> 02:14:20,660
countdown configuration.

2762
02:14:20,660 --> 02:14:23,390
Pilot Mike Smith has configured
 the cockpit instrument

2763
02:14:23,390 --> 02:14:25,750
panel displays for launch.

2764
02:14:25,750 --> 02:14:27,910
All right, we're
 clear on the ice.

2765
02:14:27,910 --> 02:14:29,310
Let's go.

2766
02:14:29,310 --> 02:14:33,980
Commander, there's word from
 level one, Challenger is a go.

2767
02:14:33,980 --> 02:14:36,020
Count down is
 continuing in 4 minutes.

2768
02:14:36,020 --> 02:14:37,410
Have a wonderful trip.

2769
02:14:37,410 --> 02:14:38,730
You're a wonderful crew.

2770
02:14:38,730 --> 02:14:39,430
All right.

2771
02:14:39,430 --> 02:14:41,260
That's great.

2772
02:14:41,260 --> 02:14:42,420
Cowabunga.

2773
02:14:42,420 --> 02:14:43,120
Double.

2774
02:14:53,710 --> 02:14:57,230
T minus 4 minutes,
 and a final purge

2775
02:14:57,230 --> 02:15:00,460
sequence of the main
 engines is underway.

2776
02:15:00,460 --> 02:15:01,840
Ground launch
 sequencer will make

2777
02:15:01,840 --> 02:15:06,220
a final check to make sure the
 vent arm is fully retracted.

2778
02:15:06,220 --> 02:15:09,830
Orbiter ground support equipment
 power bus has been turned off,

2779
02:15:09,830 --> 02:15:13,470
and the vehicle is
 now on internal power.

2780
02:15:13,470 --> 02:15:17,010
T minus 3 minutes 15 seconds.

2781
02:15:17,010 --> 02:15:18,660
Come on, Roger,
 they're about the launch.

2782
02:15:18,660 --> 02:15:20,160
No, I don't really want to.

2783
02:15:20,160 --> 02:15:20,970
Come on.

2784
02:15:20,970 --> 02:15:22,540
Sit down.

2785
02:15:22,540 --> 02:15:23,960
The pilot Mike
 Smith has cleared

2786
02:15:23,960 --> 02:15:25,800
the caution and memory system.

2787
02:15:25,800 --> 02:15:28,440
No unexpected errors reported.

2788
02:15:28,440 --> 02:15:31,560
Liquid oxygen check under way,
 and the liquid oxygen tank

2789
02:15:31,560 --> 02:15:32,670
approaching flight pressure.

2790
02:15:35,610 --> 02:15:37,490
T minus 2 minutes and counting.

2791
02:15:37,490 --> 02:15:39,870
The liquid hydrogen
 replenish has been terminated

2792
02:15:39,870 --> 02:15:42,660
and liquid hydrogen
 pressurization to flight level

2793
02:15:42,660 --> 02:15:44,010
is under way.

2794
02:15:44,010 --> 02:15:46,420
The vehicle is now isolated
 from all ground propellants

2795
02:15:46,420 --> 02:15:47,730
and crew loading equipment.

2796
02:15:47,730 --> 02:15:51,020
Activate auxiliary
 power units.

2797
02:15:51,020 --> 02:15:51,720
APUs coming on.

2798
02:15:55,090 --> 02:15:57,030
We have three good APUs.

2799
02:15:57,030 --> 02:15:59,820
Challenger is coming alive.

2800
02:15:59,820 --> 02:16:00,620
Less than two minutes.

2801
02:16:05,340 --> 02:16:08,000
T minus 1 minute 44
 seconds and counting.

2802
02:16:08,000 --> 02:16:10,860
There goes the
 beanie cap, folks.

2803
02:16:10,860 --> 02:16:14,280
Visors down, everybody,
 and welcome to space.

2804
02:16:23,200 --> 02:16:25,840
At T minus 2 minutes,
 we are anticipating

2805
02:16:25,840 --> 02:16:27,460
the launch of Challenger.

2806
02:16:27,460 --> 02:16:29,530
The cold weather has
 set us back quite a bit,

2807
02:16:29,530 --> 02:16:33,010
but they're actually nearing
 the launch, and at this point

2808
02:16:33,010 --> 02:16:34,780
the families are
 still maintaining

2809
02:16:34,780 --> 02:16:36,700
all their excitement,
 even with the delays.

2810
02:16:36,700 --> 02:16:38,080
I'm sure at this point
 the astronauts are

2811
02:16:38,080 --> 02:16:40,780
more than ready to be taking
 off of that launch pad,

2812
02:16:40,780 --> 02:16:42,670
and I'm sure
 Christa is just as--

2813
02:16:42,670 --> 02:16:43,510
as thrilled as can be.

2814
02:16:43,510 --> 02:16:47,210
I know I am just standing here
 waiting for it all to happen.

2815
02:16:47,210 --> 02:16:51,070
The cold weather actually formed
 some icicles on the launch pad

2816
02:16:51,070 --> 02:16:53,530
and they were able to
 remove some of that

2817
02:16:53,530 --> 02:16:55,180
and through some
 deicing processes

2818
02:16:55,180 --> 02:16:57,190
they have now
 cleared the launch.

2819
02:16:57,190 --> 02:16:58,870
T minus 30 seconds,
 and we've had

2820
02:16:58,870 --> 02:17:00,430
a go for auto sequence start.

2821
02:17:00,430 --> 02:17:03,500
The SRV hydraulic power
 units have started.

2822
02:17:03,500 --> 02:17:07,630
T minus 21 seconds, and
 SRB gimbal now underway.

2823
02:17:07,630 --> 02:17:11,590
T minus 15 seconds.

2824
02:17:11,590 --> 02:17:12,670
T minus 10 seconds.

2825
02:17:16,170 --> 02:17:42,590
9, 8, 7, 6, 5, 4, 3, 2, 1.

2826
02:17:51,050 --> 02:17:55,590
Oh I have slipped the
 surly bonds of earth.

2827
02:17:55,590 --> 02:18:00,820
And danced to the skies
 on laughter silvered wings.

2828
02:18:00,820 --> 02:18:04,720
High in the sun that silence
 over there i chase the shouting

2829
02:18:04,720 --> 02:18:06,080
wind alone.

2830
02:18:06,080 --> 02:18:09,980
And flung my eager craft
 through footless halls of air.

2831
02:18:09,980 --> 02:18:14,100
Up, up, the long
 delirious burning blue.

2832
02:18:14,100 --> 02:18:18,370
I've topped the wind swept
 heights with easy grace

2833
02:18:18,370 --> 02:18:21,200
where never lark
